# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batting-order-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:batting-order-baseball/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The **2011 Detroit Tigers season** was the team's 111th season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The season began on March 31 at New York against the Yankees, and the home opener was on April 8 against the Kansas City Royals.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The Tigers honored the late Sparky Anderson during the season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The Tigers sent five players to the 2011 Major League Baseball All-Star Game: starting pitcher Justin Verlander, first baseman Miguel Cabrera, catcher Alex Avila, shortstop Jhonny Peralta, and closer José Valverde.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The regular season concluded September 28 at home against the Cleveland Indians, with the Tigers holding a 95–67 record.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The season saw the team's first 11-game winning streak since 1968, and first nine-game winning streak since 1984 – both years in which the Tigers went on to win the World Series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The streak ended at 12 games on September 14.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] It consisted of four consecutive three-game sweeps over their AL Central Division rivals.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] It was the Tigers longest winning streak since the 1934 team won 14 straight.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On September 16, the Tigers clinched the AL Central Division title with a 3–1 win over the Oakland Athletics.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] It was their first American League Central Division title since they joined the division in 1998, and the team's first division title of any kind since winning the American League East in 1987.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] They became the first team of the season to qualify for the American League Division Series, and first team in either league to clinch their division.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] The Tigers clinched the division with 11 games left to play, tying the franchise record set by the 1984 team.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Justin Verlander was named both American League Cy Young Award winner and AL Most Valuable Player for an outstanding season that saw him lead the league in wins (24), strikeouts (250) and ERA (2.40).
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On October 6, the Tigers beat the New York Yankees in Game 5 of the ALDS, winning the series 3–2, and advancing to the American League Championship Series, which they lost to the Texas Rangers 4–2.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On July 3, after Tigers pitchers had given up 51 runs in the previous five games (including three games in which 14 or more runs were allowed), pitching coach Rick Knapp was fired.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Then-bullpen coach Jeff Jones was named the new pitching coach and Mike Rojas was made the new bullpen coach.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On November 4, 2010, Sparky Anderson, Tigers manager from 1979 to 1995, died at age 76.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] In his honor, the Tigers wore a memorial patch on their sleeves (seen at right), and a flag was raised in his honor on Opening Day.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] 11 jersey was officially retired by the Tigers on June 26, 2011.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] His name and number were also placed on the left-field wall at Comerica Park, joining other past Tiger greats.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Anderson is the second non-player (after broadcaster Ernie Harwell) to have his name on this wall.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Below is a chronology of highlights during the 2011 Detroit Tigers regular season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] After a remarkable September where the team went 20–6, and winning 38 of their last 54 games over the season's final two months, the Tigers finished the regular season with a 95–67 record—winning the AL Central by an astounding 15 games—and clinching the #3 seed in the American League playoffs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] It would be Detroit's first postseason appearance since 2006.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Ace starting pitcher Justin Verlander had the best season of his career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On May 7, Verlander took a perfect game against the Toronto Blue Jays into the 8th inning, and after a walk to J.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Arencibia, Verlander got his double play and went on to the 9th inning to complete his second career no-hitter.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] It was the seventh no-hitter in Tigers history.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He faced the minimum 27 batters and recorded four strikeouts with one walk and a pitch count of 108.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Verlander became the second Tigers pitcher since Virgil Trucks, and the thirtieth pitcher in the history of baseball, to throw multiple no-hitters.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Verlander also won the 100th game of his career and became the first Tiger pitcher to win 20 games in a season since Bill Gullickson in 1991.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Verlander's regular season total of 24 wins is the highest for a Tiger pitcher since Mickey Lolich won 25 in 1971.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Verlander finished the season by winning the AL pitching Triple Crown, leading the American League in wins (24), ERA (2.40) and strikeouts (250).
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On November 15, Verlander was named the AL Cy Young Award winner in a unanimous vote.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On November 21, it was announced that Verlander had also won the American League MVP Award in a much closer vote.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] 2011 was also a career best season for closer José Valverde.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On September 11, he recorded his 43rd consecutive save of the season, passing Todd Jones as the Tigers' all-time single season saves leader.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] His 45th save of the season helped the Tigers clinch the AL Central title.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] On the final day of the regular season, he recorded his 49th straight save, completing his perfect season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He recorded 2 saves against the New York Yankees in the ALDS, the second of which sent the Tigers to the ALCS.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He saved one of the Tigers' two ALCS wins.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He also won the 2011 Delivery Man of the Year Award and the 2011 AL Rolaids Relief Man of the Year Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Valverde finished fifth in the 2011 AL Cy Young Award voting, which was won by teammate Justin Verlander.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] With his Major League-best .344 batting average, Miguel Cabrera won the AL Batting Championship.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Cabrera became the first Tiger since Norm Cash and Rocky Colavito in 1961 to reach triple-digits in RBIs (105), runs (111) and walks (108).
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He also led the AL in on-base percentage (.448) and doubles (48).
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Miguel finished fifth in the voting for the AL MVP Award, which was won by teammate Justin Verlander.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He also won the Luis Aparicio Award, an award given to the best Venezuelan player each year.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Catcher Alex Avila had the best season of his young career, hitting .295 with 19 home runs and 82 RBIs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] He started in the 2011 MLB All Star game and won the Silver Slugger Award for catchers.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Super utility-man Don Kelly made his career debut as a pitcher on June 29, pitching one-third of an inning in a blowout loss to the New York Mets.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] Three days later, he made his major league debut at catcher, when he relieved Victor Martinez in the fourth inning against the San Francisco Giants.
[src:batting-order-baseball/2011-detroit-tigers-season-p01] This gave Kelly the rare distinction of playing all nine defensive positions in his major league career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge played college baseball for the Fresno State Bulldogs, and was selected by the Yankees with the 32nd pick in the first round of the 2013 MLB draft.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After making his MLB debut in 2016, Judge won AL Rookie of the Year in 2017 by unanimous vote and finished second in AL MVP voting.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He hit an AL-leading 52 home runs, temporarily setting a new MLB rookie record, and became the first rookie to win the Home Run Derby.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2022, Judge won his first MVP after setting the AL single-season home run record, breaking the 61-year-old mark held by Roger Maris.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Following the 2022 season, Judge re-signed with the Yankees on a nine-year, $360-million contract and was named the team's captain.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2024, he won his second MVP by unanimous vote, leading MLB in home runs and OPS while becoming the fastest MLB player to reach 300 career home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] That postseason, the Yankees won their first AL pennant in 15 years, but lost in the World Series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He won his third MVP and second consecutive in 2025, and also captured his first batting title.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge captained United States national team during the 2026 World Baseball Classic.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was born on April 26, 1992, in Sacramento, California.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was adopted one day later by Patty and Wayne Judge, who both worked as teachers in nearby Linden.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He has an older brother, John, who was also adopted.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Growing up, Judge was a San Francisco Giants fan.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He attended Linden High School, where he was a three-sport star.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge played as a pitcher and first baseman for the baseball team, a wide receiver for the football team, and as a center for the basketball team.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] As a sophomore, Judge earned All-Mother Lode League honors in varsity baseball as a first baseman.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The following year, he was named the Mother Lode League's Most Outstanding Player in basketball after leading Linden to its first league title since 1986.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] As a senior, he was selected as Linden High School's Athlete of the Year and received team and Mother Lode League MVP honors in all three sports, while also being named to *The Record's* All-Area first team for each.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge set school records for single-season receiving yards (969) and touchdown receptions (17), and led the basketball team in scoring at 18.2 points per game while shooting 56% from the field and averaging 12.8 rebounds and 2.3 blocks, earning Cal-Hi Sports Division IV all-state recognition.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge graduated from Linden High in 2010.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was the sole inductee into the Linden Athletic Hall of Fame in 2019.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Several colleges recruited Judge to play tight end in football, including Notre Dame, Stanford, and UCLA, but he preferred baseball.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Oakland Athletics selected him in the 31st round of the 2010 MLB draft.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He opted to enroll at California State University, Fresno, to play for the Bulldogs baseball team.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2011, Fresno State shared the Western Athletic Conference (WAC) regular season title, won the WAC Tournament, and qualified for the NCAA Division I baseball tournament.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named the WAC Freshman of the Year, earned All-WAC First Team and All-Tournament Team honors, and was selected as a Freshman All-American by Louisville Slugger.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2012, Fresno State repeated as WAC tournament champions, with Judge earning All-WAC First Team honors for the second consecutive year and another selection to the All-Tournament Team.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He finished the season tied for second in the conference with 13 stolen bases and ranked fifth with 47 runs scored.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also won the 2012 College Home Run Derby.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] That summer, he played collegiate summer baseball for the Brewster Whitecaps of the Cape Cod Baseball League, where he received the team's Citizenship Award for being a positive team member.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] As a junior in 2013, Judge led the Bulldogs in home runs (12), doubles (15), and runs batted in (36), earning All-Mountain West Conference First Team honors.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was named to the all-conference team in all three of his seasons for the Bulldogs—in the WAC in his first two seasons, and the Mountain West as a junior.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] (The Bulldogs joined the Mountain West in July 2012, before his junior season).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was honored with a jersey retirement celebration at halftime of a Fresno State football game on November 18, 2023.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The following day, the Fresno State baseball team formally retired his #29 jersey.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees drafted Judge in the first round of the 2013 MLB draft with the 32nd overall selection, a pick the team received as compensation after losing Nick Swisher in free agency.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge signed with the Yankees and received a $1.8 million signing bonus.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He tore a quadriceps femoris muscle while participating in a base running drill, which kept him out of the 2013 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge made his professional debut with the Charleston RiverDogs of the Class A South Atlantic League in 2014.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He had a .333 batting average (6th in the league), .428 on-base percentage (OBP; 3rd), .530 slugging percentage (SLG; 6th), a .958 on-base plus slugging (OPS) and hit nine home runs with 45 RBIs in 65 games for Charleston.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees promoted him to the Tampa Yankees of the Class A-Advanced Florida State League in June, where he hit .283 with a .411 OBP (2nd in the league), .442 SLG, eight home runs, and 33 RBIs in 66 games for Tampa.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the season, he played for the Scottsdale Scorpions in the Arizona Fall League, batting .278 with four home runs in 24 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees invited Judge to spring training as a non-roster player in 2015.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He began the season with the Trenton Thunder of the Double-A Eastern League.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After posting a .284/.350/.510 slash line with 12 home runs (tied for 9th in the league) in 63 games for Trenton, the Yankees promoted Judge to the Scranton/Wilkes-Barre RailRiders of the Triple-A International League in June.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was chosen to play in the 2015 All-Star Futures Game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees did not include Judge in their September call-ups.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge batted .224/.308/.373 with eight home runs in 61 games for Scranton/Wilkes-Barre.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees invited Judge to spring training in 2016, and he returned to Triple-A to began the season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named to the International League All-Star Team in 2016 but did not play in the All-Star Game after he spent a month on the disabled list due to a knee sprain.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 93 games for the RailRiders, Judge batted .270/.366/.489 with 19 home runs (4th in the league), 62 runs (tied for 8th), and 65 RBIs (tied for 7th).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge made his MLB debut on August 13, 2016, starting in right field against the Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In his first MLB at-bat, Judge hit a home run off Matt Andriese; the previous batter, Tyler Austin, also making his MLB debut, had done the same.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This marked the first time that two teammates had hit home runs in their first MLB career at-bats in the same game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge also hit a home run in his second MLB game, becoming the second Yankees player, after Joe Lefebvre in 1980, to homer in each of his first two MLB games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In his debut season, Judge played in 27 games and batted .179/.263/.345 with 15 hits, four home runs, two doubles and 10 runs batted in and he struck out 42 times in 95 plate appearances.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His season ended prematurely when he was placed on the 15-day disabled list with a grade two right oblique strain on September 13, 2016.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees named Judge their Opening Day right fielder against the Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He had his first multi-home run game on April 28 against the Baltimore Orioles to help the Yankees win 14–11, coming back from a 9–1 deficit.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] One of the home runs had a measured exit velocity of 119.4 miles per hour (192.2 km/h), the fastest exit velocity for a home run measured by Statcast since it was adopted in 2015.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] (This record would later be broken by teammate Giancarlo Stanton on August 9, 2018, when Stanton launched a home run with an exit velocity of 121.7 miles per hour (195.9 km/h).) Judge ended April with 10 home runs, tying the rookie record set by José Abreu and Trevor Story.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was named the American League's (AL) Rookie of the Month for April.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In April, he had a .303 batting average, 10 home runs, 20 RBIs, and a .411 OBP in 22 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees debuted a cheering section in the right-field seats of Yankee Stadium on May 22.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Called "The Judge's Chambers", the section spans three rows in section 104 and contains 18 seats.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Fans were chosen by the team to sit there and are outfitted with black robes, wigs, and foam gavels.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In a game against the Oakland Athletics on May 28, Judge hit his first career grand slam.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named AL Rookie of the Month once again for May.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In May, he had a .347 batting average, seven home runs, 17 RBIs, and a .441 OBP in 26 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 10, Judge hit a home run that had an exit velocity of 121.1 miles per hour (194.9 km/h), again setting a new record for the hardest measured by Statcast.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The following day, Judge went 4-for-4 with two home runs; one of the home runs traveled 496 feet (151 m), the longest home run hit that season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 12, Judge was named the AL Player of the Week.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His week ended with him leading the AL in all three Triple Crown categories.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named the AL Player of the Month for June, batting .337 with 10 home runs, 25 RBIs and a .481 OBP.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His performance in June also earned him his third consecutive AL Rookie of the Month award, the longest streak since Mike Trout won four in a row in 2012.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge had a 32-game on-base streak, including reaching base in every game in June.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 2, Judge was voted as a starting outfielder to the MLB All-Star Game, receiving 4,488,702 votes, the most of any player in the AL.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge broke Joe DiMaggio's record for most home runs hit by a Yankees rookie with his 30th on July 7.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the second rookie to hit 30 home runs before the All-Star break, following Mark McGwire in 1987, and the first Yankee to do so since Alex Rodriguez in 2007.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Before the All-Star break, Judge hit .329 with 30 home runs and 66 RBIs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won the Home Run Derby, besting Minnesota Twins third baseman Miguel Sanó 11–10 in the final round to become the first rookie to win the Derby outright.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After his performance, MLB commissioner Rob Manfred stated that Judge is a player "who can become the face of the game".
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 21, Judge hit a home run that almost travelled out of Safeco Field.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The ball was hit so hard that Statcast initially did not measure the details of the home run.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 16, Judge hit a 457-foot (139 m) home run at Citi Field that reached the third deck.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also broke a record for position players by striking out in a 33rd consecutive game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 20, Judge tied pitcher Bill Stoneman's streak of striking out in 37 consecutive games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 4, Judge became the first AL rookie with 100 walks in a season since Al Rosen in 1950, and the first MLB rookie to do so since Jim Gilliam in 1953.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 10, Judge walked for the 107th time, the most walks by a rookie in a season since Ted Williams in 1939.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During the same game, he also became the second rookie in MLB history to hit 40 home runs in a season since McGwire (1987).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He joined Babe Ruth (1920), Lou Gehrig (1927), Joe DiMaggio (1937) and Mickey Mantle (1956) as the only Yankees to hit 40 home runs in a season at age 25 or younger.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 25, Judge hit his 49th and 50th home runs, tying and surpassing Mark McGwire's single-season rookie home run record.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 30, Judge hit his 52nd home run of the season and his 33rd at Yankee Stadium, surpassing Babe Ruth's single-season record (set in 1921) for most home runs hit by a Yankees player at his home ballpark.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the conclusion of September, Judge won AL Player of the Month for the second time and Rookie of the Month for the fourth time.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge appeared in 155 games and finished the regular season slashing .284/.422/.627 with 154 hits, 52 home runs, three triples, 24 doubles, 114 RBI, 127 walks, 11 intentional walks and nine stolen bases.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He led the AL in home runs, runs scored (128), and walks (a major-league rookie record 127).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also struck out an MLB-leading 208 times, breaking the Yankees record previously set by Curtis Granderson in 2012 and a rookie record previously set by Kris Bryant in 2015.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] With the Yankees finishing the year with a 91–71 record, the team clinched a Wild Card in the postseason.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During the Wild Card Game against the Minnesota Twins, Judge hit a home run en route to an 8–4 Yankees victory.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In Game 3 of the AL Division Series (ALDS), Judge robbed Francisco Lindor of a home run, preserving the tie game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge struck out 16 times in the series, setting an ALDS record.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the Yankees defeated the Cleveland Indians in the ALDS, Judge hit three home runs for the Yankees in the AL Championship Series (ALCS).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also robbed Yulieski Gurriel of a potential home run in the Yankees' Game 7 ALCS loss to the Houston Astros.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He finished with 27 strikeouts in the postseason, a major league record at the time.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] End-of-season awards for Judge included selection as an outfielder on *Baseball America*'s All-MLB Team, the Players Choice Award for Outstanding AL Rookie, and a Silver Slugger Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was unanimously voted as the AL Rookie of the Year.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He went on to finish second in the voting for the AL Most Valuable Player Award to Jose Altuve, receiving two out of 30 first place votes.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On November 21, it was revealed that Judge had undergone arthroscopic surgery in his left shoulder for a cartilage cleanup, an injury dating back to April of that year.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On March 31, Judge made his first career start at center field in the majors.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] At 6 feet 7 inches (2.01 m) tall and weighing 282 pounds (128 kg), he became the tallest and heaviest player in baseball history to play the position.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Batting .277 with 25 home runs and 58 RBIs, Judge was named a starting outfielder for the All-Star Game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge hit a solo home run off National League starter Max Scherzer.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 26, a 93 mph fastball by Kansas City Royals pitcher Jakob Junis hit Judge on his right wrist and he left the game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Later, an MRI/CT scan revealed that he suffered a fractured ulnar styloid bone in his wrist.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] No surgery was required, and initial reports gave a three-week timetable for Judge to recover.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The injury took longer to heal than expected, with Judge missing close to two months.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 18, Judge returned to the starting lineup.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He finished the season with a .278 batting average, 27 home runs, and 67 RBIs in 112 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees beat the Oakland Athletics in the Wild Card Game but were defeated, three games to one, by the Red Sox in the ALDS.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge started the season off with a .288 batting average, five home runs, and 11 RBIs in his first 20 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] However, on April 20, Judge suffered a left oblique strain while hitting a single in the sixth inning against the Kansas City Royals.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 27, Judge hit his 17th home run of the season and 100th home run of his career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Coming in his 371st game, it made him the third-fastest MLB player to hit 100 home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge hit a home run over Fenway Park's Green Monster for the first time on September 8.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] With this home run, the 2019 Yankees set a new franchise record for team home runs in a season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2019, Judge batted .272/.381/.540, with 103 hits, 27 home runs, one triple,18 doubles and 55 RBIs in 447 plate appearances across 102 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He had the fastest average exit velocity on balls hit in play among major leaguers at 95.9 mph (154.3 km/h).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He led the league in defensive runs saved as a right fielder (19 runs saved, tied with Cody Bellinger) but did so in fewer innings (775+1⁄3 compared to 911+1⁄3 for Bellinger).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge earned the Wilson Defensive Player of the Year Award for his position in right field.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During spring training in March, Judge felt soreness in his pectoral area.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] It was revealed that he had suffered a stress fracture in his ribs and was shut down for at least two weeks.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] However, the start of the season was delayed until July.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge began the shortened 2020 season with five consecutive games with a home run (6 during the span), launching a 419-feet, 108 mph three-run shot off of Boston Red Sox pitcher Matt Hall.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His streak ended on August 3 when he went 2-for-4 without a home run.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] It was the longest home run streak by a Yankees player since Alex Rodriguez (September 4–9, 2007).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 14, Judge was placed on the 10-day injured list with a right calf strain.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 26, he was again placed on the 10-day injured list after straining the same calf the day he returned against the Atlanta Braves.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He finished the season slashing .257/.336/.554 with 26 hits, nine home runs, three doubles and 22 RBIs over 28 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the playoffs, he batted 4-for-30 with 3 home runs and 5 RBI as the Yankees lost to Tampa Bay in the ALDS.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During the week of May 10–16, Judge earned his fourth career AL Player of the Week Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge had a slash line of .571/.640/1.333 with eight runs scored, 12 hits, a double, five home runs, six RBIs, and three walks in six games (five multi-hit games and his 13th career multi-homer game).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also hit his 130th career home run, the second-most in MLB history through 460 career games, trailing only Ryan Howard (142).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On May 23, Judge recorded his first career walk-off RBI, taking a walk on a 3–1 pitch from Liam Hendriks of the Chicago White Sox.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 9, Judge recorded his 500th career hit during a game against the Houston Astros by hitting a double to left field off pitcher Brandon Bielak.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the second-fastest Yankee to 500 hits and 100 home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He accomplished the feat in his 506th game, with only Joe DiMaggio getting there faster, at 395 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named the starting right fielder in the All-Star Game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Following the All-Star Game, Judge was placed on the COVID-19 injured list after testing positive for the virus.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge returned against the Tampa Bay Rays on July 27.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 12, in the Field of Dreams game in Iowa, Judge hit two multiple-run home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also hit two home runs on September 11 against the New York Mets with his 31st and 32nd home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On October 3, the last game of the regular season, Judge recorded his first career walk-off hit, a single that scored Tyler Wade to beat Tampa Bay 1–0 and clinch a Wild Card spot for the Yankees.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the Wild Card Game, Judge became the first Yankee to be ruled out at home plate on a hit in a winner-take-all game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge finished the 2021 season batting .287/.373/.544 with 158 hits, 39 home runs, 24 doubles, 98 RBI, 75 walks, two intentional walks, and six stolen bases.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the season, Judge won a Fielding Bible Award for his defensive excellence and his second Silver Slugger Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On November 23, Judge was named to the First Team of the All-MLB Team as an outfielder.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Before the 2022 Yankees season, Judge and the Yankees were unsuccessful in negotiating a long-term contract.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] General manager Brian Cashman told ESPN that the team offered Judge $17 million in arbitration and a seven-year extension worth $213.5 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge avoided salary arbitration and signed a one-year, $19 million contract on June 24, with additional $250,000 bonuses for winning each of the MVP Award and the World Series MVP Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge slashed .293/.361/.600 with six home runs in April.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He hit his first career walk-off home run on May 10 off Toronto Blue Jays closer Jordan Romano.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won the AL Player of the Month Award for May.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During the month, Judge slashed .311/.378/.699 with 12 home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He hit his second walk-off home run on June 26 against the Houston Astros.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was elected as a starter for the All-Star Game, receiving the most fan votes of any player in the AL.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This was his second consecutive and fourth overall All-Star selection.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge slugged his third walk-off homer for the season against the visiting Kansas City Royals on July 28, tying Mickey Mantle for most by a Yankee in a season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won back-to-back AL Player of the Week Awards for the weeks ending July 24 and 31.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge also claimed the AL Player of the Month Award for July after batting .333/.436/.806 with 13 home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 30, Judge became the second-fastest player in MLB history to hit 200 home runs (behind Ryan Howard), launching a two-run shot off of Jon Heasley of the Kansas City Royals.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 29, during a game against the Los Angeles Angels, Judge hit his 50th home run for the season, coming off reliever Ryan Tepera.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became only the tenth player in MLB history and third player in Yankees franchise history to record multiple 50 home run seasons.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge hit his 55th home run during the first game of a doubleheader against the Minnesota Twins on September 7 off rookie starting pitcher Louie Varland.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the fourth player in MLB history to hit at least 55 home runs and steal at least 15 bases in a season, joining Babe Ruth (1921), Sammy Sosa (1998), and Ken Griffey Jr.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge's 60th home run came on September 20.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 28, Judge hit his 61st home run off Tim Mayza of the Toronto Blue Jays, tying Roger Maris for the most home runs in a single season in AL history.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the second game of a doubleheader (and the Yankees' second-to-last regular season game) against the Texas Rangers at Globe Life Field on October 4, Judge hit his 62nd home run off Jesús Tinoco, setting the new single-season AL home run record.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was selected as the AL Player of the Week for the week of September 29–October 5.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He claimed his third AL Player of the Month Award of the season in September.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2022, Judge led the major leagues with 62 home runs, 133 runs scored, 131 RBI (tied with Pete Alonso of the Mets), 111 walks, and batted .311/.425/.686 with 177 hits, 28 doubles, and 19 intentional walks, while stealing 16 bases in 19 attempts, in 157 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was denied the AL triple crown, as Luis Arráez of the Minnesota Twins had a batting average that was five points higher than Judge's.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won the AL MVP Award, earning 28 of 30 first-place votes.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge's 2022 campaign is considered one of the best offensive seasons in major league history.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On December 30, he was voted the Associated Press (AP) "Male Athlete of the Year" by a panel of 40 sports writers and editors from news outlets throughout the United States.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge just edged out Los Angeles Angels two-way star and 2021's winner Shohei Ohtani in voting.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was also selected as the Time Magazine Athlete of the Year.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees qualified for the postseason, facing the Cleveland Guardians in the ALDS, where Judge slashed .200/.238/.500 with two home runs, as the Yankees defeated the Guardians in five games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the ALCS, Judge hit just .063/.118/.063 with one hit and a walk as the Yankees were swept in four games by the Houston Astros, who would go on to win the World Series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the 2022 season, Judge became a free agent.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees extended the qualifying offer of a one-year contract worth $19.65 million to Judge, but he declined.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During free agency, he was pursued by the San Diego Padres and San Francisco Giants as well as the Yankees.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] By early December 2022, the Padres offered Judge over $400 million, according to Judge's agent.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees were only offering $320 million over eight years.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] A new deal with the Yankees was created in a phone call between Judge and Yankees owner Hal Steinbrenner, when Steinbrenner offered to add a ninth year and an additional $40 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] That became the foundation of an agreement that the Yankees, and Judge signed on December 20, 2022, with the nine-year, $360 million deal breaking the record for the largest free agent deal in MLB history.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In a press conference on the following day, Steinbrenner named Judge the 16th captain of the Yankees and the first since Derek Jeter had retired eight years earlier.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On 2023 MLB Opening Day at Yankee Stadium, Judge hit his first home run of the year off San Francisco Giants ace Logan Webb into Monument Park.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge went on the 10-day injured list after a mild hip strain suffered while sliding into base playing against the Minnesota Twins at Target Field on April 26.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge returned against the Oakland Athletics on May 9.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge received the AL Player of the Week Award for the week of May 15–21.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Despite missing the first week of games in May, Judge also won the AL Player of the Month Award for May after batting .342/.474/.882 with 12 home runs in 21 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 3, Judge crashed through a closed gate in the outfield wall at Dodger Stadium while recording a fly out off JD Martinez, causing a sprain to his toe and leading to him missing 42 games, with the Yankees going 19–23 in his absence.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Despite the injury, Judge was elected to the All Star Game but was unable to participate, and he was replaced in the lineup by the Texas Rangers' Adolis Garcia.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge returned against the Baltimore Orioles at Camden Yards on July 28.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 23, Judge hit three home runs, including a grand slam, against the Washington Nationals at Yankee Stadium.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He repeated the feat at home against the Arizona Diamondbacks less than a month later on September 22, becoming the first Yankee to homer three times in a game twice in a season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won his second AL Player of the Week Award of the season on September 24.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 2, Judge hit his 250th career home run (30th of the season) off of Astros ace Justin Verlander in the fifth inning.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] It was his 810th career game, setting a new record as the fastest player to reach 250 home runs in MLB history, passing marks previously set by Ryan Howard (855 games) and Ralph Kiner (871 games).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Despite missing 56 games, Judge hit 37 home runs in 2023, putting him on a 55 home run pace had he played a full season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He slashed .267/.406/.613, from 106 games, his second consecutive year with an OPS over 1.000 and his third overall.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He had 98 hits, 16 doubles, 75 RBI, 88 walks, 9 intentional walks, and 3 stolen bases (caught stealing once).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees finished the regular season in fourth place in the AL East and missed the playoffs for the first time since 2016.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge received the Roberto Clemente Award before Game 3 of the World Series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The award acknowledged his exemplary character and charity work promoting responsible youth and civic citizenship in New York and California through his ALL RISE Foundation.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was also selected to the All-MLB Team for the third successive year, this time to the second team.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] As captain, Judge appeared to take a more hands-on approach towards the Yankees organization, having conversations with Steinbrenner about the team direction and potential changes following the Yankees missing the postseason.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Following an injury-interrupted spring training, Judge started the 2024 season slowly, hitting .180 through the first three weeks of April.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge primarily played at center field early in the season but also made his first major league appearance in left field when Alex Verdugo was on paternity leave.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] By late April, Judge appeared more comfortable and improved his performance at the plate, collecting eight hits and three home runs along with six walks in the final week of the month.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was selected as the AL Player of the Week for the week of May 19, after going 10-for-20 and slugging 1.200 with three home runs and five doubles in this period.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was also selected as the AL Player of the Month for May, having hit 14 home runs and 12 doubles in the month, with 27 RBI, slashing .361/.479/.918.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This marked Judge's seventh AL Player of the Month selection, and his third consecutive May honor.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge also completed a homecoming of sorts, playing his first series at Oracle Park against the San Francisco Giants, where he went 6-for-10 with three home runs and six RBI as the Yankees swept the series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] By the end of May, Judge improved his season slash line to .277/.405/.643, with an OPS of 1.048.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] For the week ending June 9, Judge received his second AL Player of the Week award for 2024.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the six-game homestand split against the Minnesota Twins and Los Angeles Dodgers, Judge slashed .500/.630/1.200 with three home runs and 12 RBI.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Following a 3-for-4 game against the Dodgers on June 9, Judge raised his season batting average to over .300 for the first time.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] At end of June, Judge led the majors in home runs (31), RBI (82), and OPS (1.144), and he was second in the AL in batting average (.316) among qualified hitters.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won the AL Player of the Month Award again in June, for the second consecutive month, slashing .409/.514/.864, with 11 home runs and 37 RBI for the month.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 27, Judge was announced as a starting outfielder for the AL in the All-Star Game, having received the most votes.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This was the second time in three seasons that he received the most All-Star votes.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 14, batting against Chad Kuhl of the Chicago White Sox, Judge hit his 300th career home run in the Yankees' 10–2 victory.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the fastest player to ever hit 300 home runs, taking him 955 games and 3,431 at-bats, surpassing both Ralph Kiner's record by 132 games and Babe Ruth's by 400 at-bats.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the second hitter to record his 300th home run prior to his 1,000th hit.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He hit his 50th and 51st home runs of the season on August 25, becoming the fifth player in MLB history with three-plus seasons of 50 or more home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named the AL Player of the Week for the week of August 19–25, following a strong homestand against the Cleveland Guardians and Colorado Rockies.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 26, Judge collected his 1,000th career hit, a line-drive single to right field against José Ferrer at Nationals Park.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge received the August AL Player of the Month Award, his third monthly award of the season, after slashing .389/.530/.856.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 13, Judge hit a go-ahead grand slam at Yankee Stadium against the Boston Red Sox.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This ended a 16-game homerless streak, the longest of his major league career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge ended the regular season slashing .322/.458/.701, with 180 hits, 58 home runs, one triple, 36 doubles, 144 RBI, 133 walks, 20 intentional walks and 10 stolen bases from 155 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees won the ALCS against the Cleveland Guardians in five games in which Judge hit two home runs and notched five RBIs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In his first World Series, Judge went 1-for-12 with seven strikeouts in the first three games of the series as the Yankees fell into a 3–0 series deficit.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In Game 5, Judge hit his first World Series home run as the Yankees jumped out to a 5–0 lead, but a series of defensive mistakes, including Judge's first error of the year, allowed the lead to slip away as the Yankees lost the game 7–6, and thus the series in five games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the season, Judge won the AL MVP Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the second Yankee player to win the award unanimously, following Mickey Mantle in 1956.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On March 29, Judge hit three home runs and a double with eight RBIs against the Milwaukee Brewers, his third career three-homer game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On March 31, Judge was named the AL Player of the Week for the opening week of the season after going 6-for-11 and slugging 1.818 with four home runs and 11 RBIs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On April 3, Judge hit his 500th career extra-base hit with a first-inning, three-run home run off the Arizona Diamondbacks' Merrill Kelly.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge became the third-fastest Yankee to reach the milestone in terms of games played, having done so in his 999th game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the same game, Judge became the first player in MLB history with five home runs and 15 RBIs in his team's first six games of the season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On April 4 against the Pittsburgh Pirates, playing in his 1,000th game for the Yankees, Judge registered his 321st home run, equaling Babe Ruth's record for home runs in his first 1,000 Yankees games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] By the end of April, Judge was slashing .427/.521/.761 with 10 home runs and 32 RBI.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won with the AL Player of the Month Award for April, the tenth of his career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On May 30 against the Los Angeles Dodgers, Judge and Shohei Ohtani became the first reigning MVPs ever to each hit a home run in the first inning of the same game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named the AL Player of the Month again in May, after slashing .364/.453/.798, with 11 home runs on the month.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His 11th career monthly award is the most in AL history, surpassing Alex Rodriguez.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 26, Judge was announced as a starting outfielder for the AL in the All-Star Game, having received the most votes for the third time in four seasons and the second straight year.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 12, Judge hit his 350th career home run against the Chicago Cubs; he accomplished this in 1,088 games, breaking the record of 1,280 games by Mark McGwire.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 27, Judge was placed on the 10-day injury list with a flexor strain in his right elbow, following discomfort while throwing from the outfield against the Toronto Blue Jays.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was reactivated on August 5, mostly appearing as designated hitter in the following month, before making more regular appearances in the outfield from mid-September.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 9 against the Detroit Tigers, Judge hit his 359th home run, passing Yogi Berra for fifth place on the Yankees all-time home run list.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 11, two more home runs against the Tigers brought his total to 361, tying Joe DiMaggio for fourth all-time in Yankees history.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The next day, he passed DiMaggio with his 362nd against the Red Sox.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This was his 19th first-inning home run of the season, breaking a tie with Alex Rodriguez (2001) and his own mark from 2024 for the most home runs by a player in a single inning in a season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 15, Judge was named the AL Player of the Week after going 9-for-20 with a 1.760 OPS, five home runs, and five RBIs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 24, he hit two home runs against the Chicago White Sox, bringing him to the 50 home run mark in a season for the fourth time, tying Babe Ruth, Mark McGwire, and Sammy Sosa for the most such seasons in MLB history.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge and Ruth are the only Yankees to have consecutive years of 50 or more homers.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 29, Judge was named the AL Player of the Week after going 9-for-20 with four home runs, nine RBIs and an OPS of 1.693.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also won the AL Player of the Month for September after slashing .391/.440/.772 with 10 home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge finished the regular season with a .331 batting average, leading the major leagues, and winning his first career batting title.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] At 6 feet 7 inches, he became the tallest batting champion in MLB history.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He slashed .331/.457/.688 with 53 home runs, 179 hits, two triples, 30 doubles, 114 RBI, 124 walks, 36 intentional walks, and 12 stolen bases in 152 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His 53 home runs were the most ever by a batting champion.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge's 36 intentional walks broke the AL single-season record, overtaking Ted Williams' record of 34 set in the 1957 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the AL Wild Card Series against the Boston Red Sox, Judge went 4-for-11 with one walk and one RBI.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On October 7 at Yankee Stadium, with the Yankees facing being swept in the AL Division Series by the Toronto Blue Jays, Judge went 3-4 and hit the tying three-run home run off the foul pole as the Yankees came back from a 6–1 run deficit to keep the series alive.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This effort answered some of the lingering criticism of his previously underwhelming postseason performances, which had amplified after he had struck out with the bases loaded in the series opener.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge ended the postseason slashing .500/.581/.692 with 13 hits, one home run, two doubles and seven RBI across seven games as the Yankees were eliminated by the Blue Jays in four games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won his third career and second consecutive AL MVP award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In a tight race, Judge received 17 first-place votes, 4 more than Cal Raleigh.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge began the 2026 MLB season by striking out four times against the San Francisco Giants on Opening Night.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On April 14, Judge hit two home runs against the Los Angeles Angels at Yankee Stadium.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On May 24, Judge hit his fourth career walk-off home run to defeat the Tampa Bay Rays, ending a career-high 11 game homerless streak.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 5, Judge was diagnosed with a stress fracture on the right side of his first rib, which was suspected to have been suffered during a game against the Houston Astros approximately six weeks previously.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was placed on the ten-day injured list from June 2 and was expected to miss at least four weeks.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge did not compete in the 2023 World Baseball Classic (WBC), choosing instead to focus on preparing for his season with the Yankees, given his recent contract and captaincy.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On April 14, 2025, Judge was named captain of Team USA ahead of the 2026 WBC.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Manager Mark DeRosa announced the decision on MLB Network, with Judge joining the broadcast to express his excitement: "Now, getting a chance to have 'USA' across my chest and represent all the great people in our country and represent what this country means, it's a great opportunity.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] At the WBC, Judge posted a slash line of .222/.364/.481, slugging two home runs with five RBIs and six hits across seven games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Highlights included homering on his very first swing of the tournament — a 405-foot, 106.5 mph two-run blast against Brazil — and a pair of standout defensive plays from right field, throwing out runners attempting to advance to third base.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He threw out Joey Ortiz against Mexico in pool play, then did the same to Fernando Tatis Jr. against the Dominican Republic in the semi-final game with his throw clocked at 95.7 mph.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge and Team USA advanced to the championship game against Venezuela, but fell short by a score of 3–2, marking back-to-back runner-up finishes for the U.S. in the WBC.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The offense for the U.S. went quiet in the game, with Judge going 0-for-4 with three strikeouts.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge is listed at 6 feet 7 inches (2.01 m) and 282 pounds (128 kg).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Due to his large size and strength, he has elicited comparisons to teammate Giancarlo Stanton, as well as former MLB players Richie Sexson, Dave Winfield, and Willie Stargell.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His power output is historically significant: he is one of only eight players in MLB history to record an OPS+ above 200 in three seasons.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He is also one of just 14 players in MLB history to slug above .700 in a season with a minimum of 550 plate appearances.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He is the fourth player ever to produce four seasons with 50 or more home runs, alongside Ruth, Sammy Sosa, and Mark McGwire.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Since Statcast began tracking exit velocity in 2015, Judge broke the record for the hardest-hit home run with a 121.1 mph blast on June 10, 2017, against the Baltimore Orioles; although later surpassed, it ranked fifth as of 2025.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge and Miguel Sanó are the only MLB players since 2015 to hit multiple home runs measuring at least 495 feet.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge has been credited as a team leader both on and off the field.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He has a number of rituals before, during, and after games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During his 2017 rookie season, Judge kept a note on his phone that read ".179", his batting average with the Yankees in 2016, and looked at it daily as a source of motivation.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge has worn the unusual uniform number of 99 since it was given to him during 2016 spring training (higher numbers are typically given to young players who are not expected to make the final regular-season roster).
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2016, Judge stated that he would have preferred either No.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] 44 (retired by the Yankees to honor Reggie Jackson) or No.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] 35 but was not sure whether he would switch if the latter two were to become available.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] MLB along with the MLB Players Association, created Players Weekend to let players "express themselves while connecting with their past in youth baseball".
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] From August 25–27, 2017, players wore alternate team jerseys inspired by youth league designs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] They also had the option to replace their last names with their nicknames on their jersey nameplates, and the vast majority of players did so.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge chose the nickname "All Rise" (given to him by former teammate Todd Frazier) to be worn on the back of his jersey nameplate.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] For the 2018 Players Weekend, Judge chose to just have his last name on the back of his jersey.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During the 2019 event, Judge chose his own nickname, "BAJ", an abbreviation of "Big Aaron Judge".
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge married his wife in December 2021 at a private ceremony in Maui.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] They met at Linden High School and both attended Fresno State University.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Their first child was born in January 2025.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge has two pet dachshunds named Gus and Penny.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He grew up going to a Methodist church and has posted about his faith on his social media accounts.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge is the founder of the ALL RISE Foundation.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge's mother, Patty, serves as its executive director and president.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] At the beginning of his career, Judge had contracts with Rawlings, Under Armour, and Fanatics.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After his 2017 rookie season, Judge signed a multi-year endorsement deal with Pepsi.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge endorsed Under Armour gear from 2014 until the 2018 season, when he signed an endorsement deal with Adidas.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In August 2023, Judge signed a shoe deal with Nike-owned Jordan Brand, becoming the fifth active MLB player to do so.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] For the 2023 season, *Legends Hospitality*, the concessions company at Yankee Stadium, announced "The 99 Burger", a California-inspired food item named after Judge's uniform number.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In March 2024, Judge was named the face of a new Ralph Lauren fragrance, "Polo Est.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] 67 Eau de Toilette" and its "Design Your Dreams" ad campaign.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In April 2024, Judge agreed to endorse energy drink Prime.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2025, Judge became the first active MLB player featured on a Big League Chew pouch when he appeared on the limited-edition "Grand Slam Grape" flavor.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge appeared on the cover of the May 15, 2017, edition of *Sports Illustrated* with the title "All Rise"*.* That same day, Judge appeared on an episode of *The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon* where he posed undercover in Bryant Park to ask Yankee fans questions about himself.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On November 6, 2017, Judge was named the cover athlete for *MLB The Show 18*.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge appeared on a 23-second skit on rapper Logic's 2022 album *Vinyl Days* named after himself.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2024, Judge and his two pet dachshunds guest starred on an episode of *Rubble & Crew*, a *Paw Patrol* spin-off.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge also participated in the 2026 FIFA World Cup draw on December 5, 2025.
[src:batting-order-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On January 27, 2026, Judge was announced as the cover athlete for *MLB The Show 26*, becoming just the second player to appear on the game's cover twice.
[src:batting-order-baseball/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:batting-order-baseball/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:batting-order-baseball/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:batting-order-baseball/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:batting-order-baseball/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:batting-order-baseball/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:batting-order-baseball/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Near the end of his career, Kaline also played as first baseman and, in his last season, was the Tigers' designated hitter.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He retired soon after reaching the 3,000 hit milestone late in the 1974 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Immediately after retiring from playing, he became the Tigers' TV color commentator, a position he held from 1975 until 2002.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline worked for the Tigers as a front office assistant from 2003 until his death in 2020.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline was born and raised in Baltimore, Maryland, the son of Naomi (Morgan) and Nicholas Kaline.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Several of his relatives played semi-professional baseball, but no one in the family had graduated from high school.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] When he was eight years old, Kaline developed osteomyelitis and had two inches of bone removed from his left foot.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] The surgery left him with scarring and permanent deformity, but he was an outstanding pitcher in youth baseball.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline had learned to throw a fastball, changeup and curveball by the age of nine.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline attended Baltimore's Southern High School, where he starred in basketball and also played football until he sustained a cheek injury.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] When he tried out for the baseball team, there was no room on the pitching staff so Kaline moved to the outfield.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He earned all-state honors in baseball all four years.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline said that he was a poor student but that he was well-liked by his teachers.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He said that his teachers passed him, believing he would become a baseball player.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] At the time of Kaline's signing, the bonus rule implemented by Major League Baseball was still in effect.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] The rule stipulated that when a major league team signed a player to a contract with a signing bonus in excess of $4,000 ($58,000 today), the team was required to keep that player on their 25-man active roster for two full seasons.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] If the team failed to comply with the rule, they would lose the rights to that player's contract, and the player would then be exposed to the waiver wire.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] As Kaline had received a bonus of $15,000 ($216,000 today), he bypassed the minor leagues and joined the Tigers directly from high school.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He made his major league debut on June 25, 1953 in Philadelphia as a late-inning replacement for outfielder Jim Delsing.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline wore number 25 during his rookie campaign, but asked teammate Pat Mullin for his No.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] 6 when he retired after the 1953 season ended.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline wore the number for the rest of his major league playing career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In 1955, at age 20, Kaline ended the season with a .340 batting average, becoming the youngest player ever to win the American League (AL) batting title.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] No 20-year-old major league player had won a batting title since Ty Cobb in 1907.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] During the 1955 season, Kaline became the 13th man in major league history to hit two home runs in the same inning, became the youngest to hit three home runs in one game, and finished the year with 200 hits, 27 home runs and 102 runs batted in (RBIs).
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] His 200 hits led the major leagues, and he also led the American League with 321 total bases.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline finished second to Yogi Berra in the American League's 1955 Most Valuable Player Award voting.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He was selected to the Major League Baseball All-Star Game, the first in a string of consecutive All-Star selections that lasted through 1967.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline followed in 1956 with a .314 batting average, 27 home runs and a career-high 128 RBIs, finishing third in the AL MVP voting.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He led the league in outfield assists with 18 in 1956 and again in 1958 with 23.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In 1957, he won the first of what would be ten Gold Glove Awards over the next eleven seasons.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline was out for several games in 1958 after he was hit by a pitch.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He missed several games in 1959 after he was hit by a thrown ball and sustained a fracture in his cheekbone.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline had been knocked out from the blow and initial speculation was that he could miss six weeks of the season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline ended up missing only 18 games, and finished the 1959 season with a .327 batting average and 27 home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He also led the AL in slugging percentage (.530) and OPS (.940).
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] By the time of his 26th birthday, Kaline had accumulated 1,200 hits, the third highest total by a 25-year-old player in MLB history, behind only Ty Cobb (1,433) and Mel Ott (1,249).
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Following the departure of Harvey Kuenn, Kaline played the entire 1960 season in center field, the only time of his career he would do so.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In 1961, the Tigers acquired Bill Bruton from the Milwaukee Braves to play center field, allowing Kaline to move back to right field.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In 1961, Kaline led the majors with 41 doubles and hit .324 to finish second in the AL batting race (behind teammate Norm Cash).
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] The Tigers won 101 games, to date the third-highest win total in team history, but still finished eight games behind a New York Yankees team that was led by the home run heroics of Roger Maris (61) and Mickey Mantle (54).
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline began the 1962 season hitting .345 with 13 home runs and 38 RBIs in 35 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] On May 26 of that season, he sustained a broken collarbone while making a game-ending catch on a ball hit by New York's Elston Howard.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He missed 57 games due to the injury and Detroit was unable to seriously compete for a pennant due to his absence.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] When healthy, Kaline was great in 1962, hitting a career-high 29 home runs and driving in 94 runs in only 100 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] By late March 1963, Kaline said that he felt good and he was hitting .373 in 53 spring training at-bats.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In the 1963 regular season, Kaline hit .312 with 27 home runs and 101 RBIs, finishing second to Elston Howard in the American League's Most Valuable Player Award voting.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline experienced pain in his left foot, the one that had been affected by osteomyelitis as a child, throughout the 1964 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] His batting average dropped to .293 that season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline tried to ignore the pain, but he saw physicians who thought he was suffering from gout and administered injections.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Still in pain the following season, Kaline saw an orthopedic surgeon who prescribed corrective shoes.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] "I feel so much better than I did before, that it's ridiculous", Kaline said by June 1965.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Sportswriter Milton Gross described Kaline's deformed foot, saying, "The pinky and middle finger don't touch the ground.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] The first and third toes overlap the second and the fourth is beginning to overlap the big toe, which has begun to bend to the left.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In 1966, Kaline tied his career high with 29 home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In the summer of 1967, the normally calm Kaline broke a bone in his hand when he struck a baseball bat against a bat rack.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] When he returned, the Tigers were in a four-team pennant race, but the team finished the season one game behind the first place Boston Red Sox.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline missed two months of the 1968 season with a broken arm, but he returned to the lineup when Tiger manager Mayo Smith benched shortstop Ray Oyler and sent center fielder Mickey Stanley to play shortstop to make room for Kaline in the outfield.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] ESPN later called Smith's move one of the ten greatest coaching decisions of the century.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Louis Cardinals won three of the first four games of the series and were leading Game 5 by a score of 3–2 in the seventh inning, when Kaline hit a bases loaded single to drive in two runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] The Tigers won that game, and then won Game 6 in a blowout.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline had two hits, two runs scored and three RBI in the Tigers' 10-run third inning of Game 6.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Detroit went on to win Game 7 for their first world championship since 1945.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In his only World Series appearance, Kaline hit .379 with two home runs and eight RBIs in seven games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] For their victory, Kaline and his teammates each received bonus checks of $10,000 (at a time when Kaline's salary was "about $70,000").
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] The 1969 Tigers could not repeat the magic of their World Series triumph, as they won 90 games but still finished 19 games behind the Baltimore Orioles in the newly-formed American League East division.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline hit .272 with 21 home runs in 131 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] It was the last season of his career that he reached 20 homers.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In 1970, Kaline sustained a freak, near-fatal injury in an outfield collision.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In a game at Milwaukee's County Stadium on May 30, against the Milwaukee Brewers, Kaline collided with center fielder Jim Northrup as they both pursued a fly ball.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline fell to the warning track and immediately began to choke; on impact, his jaw had gotten locked and his tongue obstructed his breathing.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Alertly, left fielder Willie Horton rushed over and pried opened Kaline's mouth, clearing his airway and likely saving his life.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline was carried out on a stretcher and spent the night in hospital as a precaution.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Later on, he said that he could not remember the incident.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] After hitting .294 in 1971, Kaline became the first Tiger to sign a $100,000 ($794,988 in today's dollars) contract.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He had turned down a pay raise from $95,000 to $100,000 the previous year, saying he did not feel like he deserved it after hitting .278 with 16 home runs in 1970.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Detroit contended all season for the 1972 pennant, trailing the Red Sox by a half-game before a series against them to end the regular season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline batted eight times in two games, registering five hits and three runs scored.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Detroit won those first two games and clinched the AL East pennant.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline batted .313 in 106 games in 1972, topping .300 for the first time since 1967.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] The Tigers lost the 1972 American League Championship Series to the Oakland Athletics that year after Reggie Jackson stole home in the decisive fifth game of the series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In March 1973, Kaline won the Roberto Clemente Award in recognition of the honor he brought to baseball on and off the field.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] On September 24, 1974, Kaline became the 12th player in MLB history to reach the 3,000 hit milestone, when he hit a double off the Orioles' Dave McNally.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] After reaching the milestone, Kaline announced that he would retire at season's end.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] I may miss spring training", Kaline said after his last game on October 3, 1974.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In his final major league season, he was used exclusively as a designated hitter, batting .262 with 13 home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He batted over .300 nine times in his career to finish with a lifetime batting average of .297 and hit 25 or more home runs seven times in his career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline also holds Tiger career records for games played (2,834), walks (1,277), and sacrifice flies (104).
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He had more walks than strikeouts (1,020).
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline was a good pinch hitter in his career, batting .311 (37-for-119) in that capacity with two home runs and 23 RBI.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] His highest season strikeout total came in his final season, with 75.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Prior to that, Kaline never struck out more than 66 times in a season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Among position players, Kaline ranks 29th all-time (15th among outfielders) in Wins Against Replacement (WAR) with a career mark of 92.8.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Defensively, Kaline finished his career with an overall .987 fielding percentage.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In his first full season (1954), he recorded 16 outfield assists, including three in one game (July 7 against the Chicago White Sox).
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He recorded 84 outfield assists between 1954 and 1958, posting a career-high 23 in 1958.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] After that season, baserunners rarely tested his arm, and his assist numbers dropped.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1980, becoming the tenth player in history to be inducted in his first year of eligibility.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He was named on 340 of the 385 ballots (88.3%) cast by sportswriters.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline and Duke Snider were the only candidates elected by the sportswriters in 1980.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline later said, "I really never thought I would choose an individual thing that happened just to me over a team thing like the World Series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline was honored by the Tigers as the first of their players to have his uniform number (6) retired.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Versatile and well-rounded, he won ten Gold Glove Awards (1957–59 and 1961–67) for excellence in the field and appeared in the All-Star game 15 times (1955–67, 1971, 1974).
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In 1999, Kaline was ranked number 76 on *The Sporting News* list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players, and was nominated as a finalist for the Major League Baseball All-Century Team.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In 2020, *The Athletic* ranked Kaline at number 51 on its "Baseball 100" list, complied by sportswriter Joe Posnanski.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] In 2022, as part of their SN Rushmore project, *The Sporting News* named Kaline on their "Detroit Mount Rushmore of Sports", along with Detroit Red Wings hockey player Gordie Howe, Detroit Lions football player Barry Sanders, and Detroit Pistons basketball player Isiah Thomas.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Cherry Street, which ran behind the left-field stands at Tiger Stadium, was renamed Kaline Drive in his honor in 1970.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] On September 27, 1999, when Detroit played its last game at Tiger Stadium against the Kansas City Royals, Kaline was invited to appear in uniform and present the last lineup card to the umpires.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He did so along with George Brett, former Kansas City Royals' great and fellow Hall of Famer.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline was regarded as a well-rounded player by his contemporaries.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Baltimore Orioles third baseman Brooks Robinson said of him, "There have been a lot of great defensive players.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] The fella who could do everything is Al Kaline.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He was just the epitome of what a great outfielder is all about – great speed, catches the ball and throws the ball well." Manager Billy Martin once said, "I have always referred to Al Kaline as 'Mister Perfection'.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He does it all — hitting, fielding, running, throwing — and he does it with that extra touch of brilliancy that marks him as a super ballplayer...
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] The 1993 Major League Baseball All-Star Game was dedicated to Kaline on the occasion of the 35th anniversary of his hometown's only other Midsummer Classic.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline, along with Leon Day and former Baltimore Orioles star Brooks Robinson, threw out the ceremonial first pitch to end the pregame ceremonies.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline's ceremonial first pitch was caught by future Detroit Tiger Ivan Rodriguez, who was starting his All-Star debut.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Starting in 2003, Kaline served as a special assistant to Tigers President/CEO/General Manager Dave Dombrowski, and his duties included coaching/mentoring outfielders during spring training.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Former Tigers teammate Willie Horton also holds this position, and the two threw out the first pitch of the 2006 World Series at Comerica Park.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline continued in his assistant role until his death in 2020.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] His 67 years with one team was one of the longest tenures in MLB history.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Because of his lengthy career and longtime association with the Tigers organization, Kaline's nickname was "Mr.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Tiger." Kaline's grandson Colin Kaline was selected by the Tigers in the 25th round of the 2007 MLB draft.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He did not sign, choosing to play baseball at Florida Southern College.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] The team drafted him again in the 2011 MLB draft, this time in the 26th round.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] He played in the low minor leagues with the Detroit organization in 2011–12.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline married his high school sweetheart, Madge Louise Hamilton, in 1954.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] August 21, 1957) and Michael Keith Kaline (b.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Michael played college baseball at Miami University and is the father of Colin Kaline, who had a short Minor League career and was a college coach.
[src:batting-order-baseball/al-kaline] Kaline died in his home in Bloomfield Hills, Michigan, on April 6, 2020; the cause of death was not reported.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell won the 1984 World Series championship over his hometown San Diego Padres, earning Series MVP honors.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] His team also won an American League East division championship in 1987.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Although his arm was not overpowering, he had a quick release and made accurate throws, ultimately winning four Gold Glove awards.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell's defense perfectly complemented his double-play partner, Lou Whitaker.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] The two formed the longest continuous double-play combination in major league history, playing 19 seasons together.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] At the plate, Trammell was one of the best-hitting shortstops of his era and won three Silver Slugger awards.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell later served as the Tigers' manager from 2003 through 2005.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He also served as the interim manager for the Arizona Diamondbacks during the final three games of the 2014 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 2018.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell attended Kearny High School in San Diego, California and played American Legion Baseball.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He was named the 1989 American Legion Graduate of the Year.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] The Detroit Tigers selected him in the second round of the 1976 MLB draft.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Both players became regulars at their positions the following season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell batted .300 in 1980 as he made the All-Star team for the first time.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In 1983, he batted .319 with 14 home runs, 66 runs batted in and 30 stolen bases.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Having hit .258 in both 1981 and 1982, Trammell won the 1983 MLB Comeback Player of the Year Award in the American League (AL).
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell and Whitaker made a cameo appearance on the television show *Magnum, P.I.*, starring Tom Selleck, during the 1983 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Selleck's character was a Tigers fan, as is Selleck himself.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] The Tigers enjoyed a championship-winning season in 1984, when they started the season 35–5 and led the AL wire-to-wire en route to winning the World Series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Despite a season-long battle with tendinitis in his shoulder that caused him to miss 23 regular season games, Trammell finished fifth in the AL batting race with a .314 mark and ranked eighth in on-base percentage (.382).
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In the AL Championship Series against the Kansas City Royals, he hit .364 with one home run and three RBI.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Finally, in the World Series, he hit .450 (9-for-20) against the San Diego Padres, including a pair of two-run home runs that accounted for all of the Tigers' scoring in a Game 4 victory.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Detroit won the series 4–1, and Trammell was named World Series MVP.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In 1985, after two consecutive years of batting not lower than .314, Trammell was hampered by injuries and posted only a .258 batting average.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He underwent postseason surgery on his left knee and right shoulder.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] The following season, a fully healthy Trammell hit 21 homers and stole 25 bases, becoming only the second player in Detroit history to hit 20+ home runs and steal 20+ bases in the same season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] (Kirk Gibson was the other, while Curtis Granderson and Robbie Grossman later joined the club.) Trammell also set a career-high with 75 RBI.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In 1987, asked by manager Sparky Anderson to replace the departed Lance Parrish as cleanup hitter, Trammell responded with his best major league season, hitting a career-high 28 home runs to go with a .343 batting average (ranking third in the AL).
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In September, he batted .416 with six homers and 17 RBI and put together an 18-game hitting streak in which he hit .457.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] On the penultimate day of the regular season, he hit a walk-off single against the Toronto Blue Jays to help his team take the AL East division lead, which they clinched the next day.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He became the first Tiger to collect 200 hits and 100 RBI in the same season since Al Kaline did it in 1955.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell also became the first shortstop to hit at least .340 with 20+ home runs and 100+ RBI in a season in big league history.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Despite his efforts, Trammell finished second to Toronto's George Bell in the MVP voting (332–311).
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell followed up with a .311 season in 1988, though a stint on the disabled list limited him to 128 games that year.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Following the 1990 season, in which he hit .304 with 89 RBI in 146 games, Trammell suffered a long string of injuries that reduced his production over his final years.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In 1991, knee and ankle injuries limited Trammell to 101 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] During the following season, he played in 29 games before breaking his right ankle and missing the remainder of the 1992 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He hit .329 in a resurgent 1993 season but was ineligible to be ranked among the AL batting leaders because he only had 447 plate appearances.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In his final five seasons, Trammell averaged 76 games played after averaging 140 games played the first 13 seasons of his career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] From 1993 to 1996, Trammell saw less time at shortstop in favor of Travis Fryman and eventually Chris Gomez and Andújar Cedeño.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He instead saw playing time at several positions, including shortstop, third base, second base, left field, center field, and designated hitter.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell retired following the 1996 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In his 20-year career, Trammell batted over .300 seven times, ending with a career average of .285 and 185 home runs with 1,003 RBI, 1,231 runs, 2,365 hits, 412 doubles, 55 triples, 236 stolen bases and 850 walks in 2,293 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He compiled a .977 fielding percentage at shortstop, his primary position.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In 2001, Trammell was rated as the ninth-best shortstop of all time in "The New Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract", placing him higher than fourteen Hall of Fame shortstops.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In subsequent years, Trammell's candidacy for the Hall of Fame picked up increasing support from the sabermetric community.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] His boost in later years was likely due to voters being more receptive to advanced metrics, such as wins above replacement.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell was on his 15th and final Baseball Writers' Association of America ballot in 2016, failing to earn enough for induction.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell was one of the last candidates to be allowed on the ballot for 15 years after the BBWAA reduced eligibility to ten years, and would next be considered for the Veterans Committee Expansion starting from 2017.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] On December 10, 2017, he was elected to the Hall of Fame by the Modern Baseball Committee alongside teammate Jack Morris.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In 1998, Trammell was elected into the National Polish-American Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Alan Trammell's jersey #3 was retired by the Tigers in a ceremony on August 26, 2018.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] His name and number were added to the brick wall in left-center field at Comerica Park, alongside Charlie Gehringer (#2), Hank Greenberg (#5), Al Kaline (#6), Sparky Anderson (#11), Hal Newhouser (#16), Willie Horton (#23), Ty Cobb (no number) and Jack Morris (#47).
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Jackie Robinson's #42 was retired throughout baseball in 1997.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Double-play mate Lou Whitaker had his #1 retired in 2022, and it now fittingly stands to the right of Trammel's on the outfield wall.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] After his retirement, Trammell coached for Detroit (1999, hitting coach) and the San Diego Padres (2000–2002, first base coach) before becoming a manager.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell was named the manager of a struggling Tigers team on October 9, 2002.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] The team lost 119 games in his first season in 2003, an American League record at the time, before posting a 72–90 record in 2004.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In the 2005 season, however, the team's record regressed slightly, finishing 71–91.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] During Trammell's three years as manager, the Tigers compiled a record of 186–300.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] During the 2003 season, Detroit nearly matched the modern MLB record of 120 losses, set by the expansion New York Mets (40–120) in 1962.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] The Tigers won five of their last six games to avoid the distinction.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] The Mets' major league record and Tigers' American League record for losses was later surpassed by the 2024 Chicago White Sox.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] On October 3, 2005, the Tigers released Trammell after three seasons in which the organization failed to post a winning record.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell was replaced by Jim Leyland on October 4, 2005.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Leyland led Detroit to a 24-game improvement in the regular season, an AL pennant, and a World Series appearance in 2006.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Leyland himself attributed a degree of the success that the Tigers saw in the 2006 postseason to Trammell's efforts in the three years prior.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In October 2006, Trammell returned to Comerica Park for the first time since his firing to participate, along with Sparky Anderson, in pregame festivities prior to Game 2 of the World Series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell was showered with a lengthy standing ovation from Detroit baseball fans upon taking the field.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] After being replaced by Leyland, Trammell turned down an offer to stay with the Tigers as a special assistant, instead opting to sit out 2006.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] In October 2006, he agreed to join the Chicago Cubs as a bench coach for the 2007 season, a possible precursor to an eventual return to managing a major league club.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] During the four-game suspension of Lou Piniella in 2007, Trammell was acting manager of the Chicago Cubs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell was passed over for the Cubs' managerial position when Lou Piniella retired midway through the 2010 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell was named bench coach of the Arizona Diamondbacks in October 2010, joining his former teammate Kirk Gibson.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Gibson had previously been Trammell's bench and hitting coach with the Tigers.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He and Gibson were fired on September 26, 2014, though Trammell stayed on for the final three games of the season to serve as the interim manager.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He had a record of one win and two losses with Arizona.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] On November 3, 2014, it was announced that Trammell would return to Detroit as a special assistant to Tigers' general manager Dave Dombrowski.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] During the 2015 season Trammell served as interim first-base coach when Omar Vizquel temporarily left the team on bereavement leave.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] He wore #4 during this time, as Ian Kinsler was wearing Trammell's familiar #3.
[src:batting-order-baseball/alan-trammell] Trammell continued to serve as a special assistant to Tigers' GM Al Avila until Avila was dismissed in August 2022, and Avila was replaced as GM by Jeff Greenberg in September 2023, with Trammell maintaining his special assistant role.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols was a highly regarded hitter who possessed a "combination of contact hitting ability, patience and raw power." He was the National League (NL) Most Valuable Player (MVP) in 2005, 2008, and 2009 and is an 11-time All-Star (2001, 2003–2010, 2015, 2022).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was a six-time Silver Slugger and won two Gold Glove awards at first base in his career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols twice led the NL in home runs and once each in batting average, doubles, and runs batted in (RBIs).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols surpassed 3,000 career hits, becoming the 32nd MLB player to reach that milestone.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] During his final season, Pujols moved into second place all-time for career RBIs and total bases and became the fourth player with 700 career home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols was born and raised in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic, mostly by his grandmother, America Pujols, and 10 of his uncles and aunts.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] His father, Bienvenido Pujols, was a softball pitcher who struggled with alcoholism.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols often had to take his father home when he got drunk following games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Growing up, Pujols practiced baseball using limes for balls and a milk carton for a glove.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols, his father, and his grandmother immigrated in 1996 to Washington Heights in New York City, where Pujols witnessed a shooting at a bodega.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Partly because of the shooting, they moved two months later to Independence, Missouri, to join some relatives.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols played baseball at Fort Osage High School in Independence and was named an All-State athlete twice.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] As a senior, he was walked 55 times intentionally, but he still hit eight home runs in 33 at-bats.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] One of his home runs travelled 450 feet (140 m).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] After graduating from high school a semester early in December 1998, he was given a baseball scholarship to Maple Woods Community College.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit a grand slam and turned an unassisted triple play in the first game of his only college season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Playing shortstop, he batted .461 with 22 home runs as a freshman before deciding to enter the Major League Baseball (MLB) draft.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Few teams were interested in Pujols because of uncertainty about his age, which position he would play, and his build.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Tampa Bay Rays scout Fernando Arango recommended that his team sign Pujols, and quit his job when Tampa Bay failed to do so.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols was not drafted until the 13th round of the 1999 Major League Baseball (MLB) draft, when the St.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Louis Cardinals selected him with the 402nd overall pick.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols initially turned down a $10,000 bonus and spent the summer playing for the Hays Larks of the Jayhawk Collegiate League (a summer league in the National Baseball Congress).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] When the Cardinals increased their bonus offer to $60,000, he signed.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols began his minor league career in 2000 playing third base with the Peoria Chiefs of the single-A Midwest League.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .324 with 128 hits, 32 doubles, six triples, 17 home runs and 84 RBI, in 109 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was voted the league's Most Valuable Player and named to the All-Star team.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols also played 21 games with the Potomac Cannons in the high-A Carolina League that year, batting .284 with 23 hits, nine doubles, one triple, two home runs and 10 RBI.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He finished the 2000 season with the Memphis Redbirds in the AAA Pacific Coast League (PCL), and after appearing in three regular season games with them, he batted .367 in the playoffs and was named the postseason Most Valuable Player (MVP) as the Redbirds won their first PCL title.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] According to La Russa, he and the rest of Cardinals management were impressed enough by Pujols that they decided to promote him to the big league club even before Bonilla's injury.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Cardinals executive John Vuch backed this up, calling the link between Pujols and Bonilla an "old wives' tale" and stating that the competition for the last roster spot was actually between Bonilla and John Mabry.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Although the team did not require Pujols to fill any particular position, the Cardinals activated him to the Opening Day roster, and he started all season at third base, right field, left field, or first base.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On Opening Day against the Colorado Rockies on April 2, Pujols became the first major league player born in the 1980s.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In that game, he recorded his first career hit, a single against pitcher Mike Hampton in an 8–0 loss.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Four days later, he had three hits and three RBI — including his first home run — against the Arizona Diamondbacks' Armando Reynoso in a 12–9 win.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On April 9, in his first career home game, Pujols hit a two-run home run in his first at bat against Denny Neagle of Colorado.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Through 2015, he was one of three players to hit 20 or more home runs in their rookie year before July, along with Wally Berger (1930) and Joc Pederson (2015).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] At midseason, Pujols became the first Cardinals rookie since Luis Arroyo in 1955 to make the All-Star Game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He finished the season batting .329 (sixth in the league) with 194 hits (fifth in the league), 47 doubles (fifth in the league), 37 home runs, and 112 runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] His 37 home runs led the Cardinals, topping Jim Edmonds' 30 and McGwire's 29.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was named the National League (NL) Silver Slugger Award winner for the third base position, and he finished fourth in NL Most Valuable Player (MVP) voting, behind Barry Bonds, Sammy Sosa and Luis Gonzalez.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was unanimously named the NL Rookie of the Year after setting an NL rookie record with 130 RBI's (fifth in the league) and becoming the fourth MLB rookie to hit .300 with 30 home runs, 100 runs, and 100 RBI's.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals finished the 2001 season with a 93–69 record and advanced to the playoffs as the National League wild card team.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The team advanced to the NL Division Series (NLDS).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 2 on October 10, Pujols hit a game-winning two-run home run against Diamondbacks pitcher Randy Johnson in a 4–1 victory.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals, however, were eliminated in five games, and Pujols had just two hits in 18 at-bats.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] After playing several positions in 2001, Pujols spent most of 2002 in left field.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He began the season batting cleanup but was moved in May to the third spot in the lineup, where he remained for the rest of his Cardinals career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit his 30th home run and 100th RBI of the season in a 5–4 loss to the Cincinnati Reds in August, making him the sixth Cardinal to have back-to-back 30-home-run seasons and the second Cardinal (the other was Ray Jablonski) to start his career with back-to-back 100-RBI seasons.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The following month, Pujols hit a game-winning two-run single against Pete Munro in a 9–3 victory over the Houston Astros that gave the Cardinals the NL Central title.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished the year batting .314 (seventh in the NL) with 185 hits (tied for fourth in the NL), 40 doubles (eighth in the NL), 34 home runs (10th in the NL), 118 runs scored (second in the NL to Sosa's 122), and 127 RBI's (second in the NL).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He became the first player in major league history to hit over .300 with at least 30 home runs, 100 runs scored, and 100 RBI in his first two seasons.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished second in MVP voting to Bonds, becoming the first Cardinal since Stan Musial to finish in the top four in MVP voting for consecutive seasons.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols' contributions helped the Cardinals finish third in home runs and second in batting average and RBI; the Cardinals' pitching staff also finished fourth in ERA.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals again reached the playoffs, and Pujols had three hits and three RBI in a three-game sweep of the Diamondbacks in the 2002 NLDS.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The team advanced to the 2002 NL Championship Series (NLCS), but lost in five games to the San Francisco Giants.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols had five hits, one home run and two RBI in the series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Five Cardinals were named to the All-Star Game in 2003 while Pujols led the NL in votes.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] It was the first of eight straight seasons that Pujols would reach the All-Star Game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] From July 12 to August 16, Pujols had a 30-game hitting streak, tied for the second-longest in Cardinals' history with Musial and behind only Rogers Hornsby's 33-game streak.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On July 20, Pujols hit his 100th career home run, a game-winner in a 10–7 victory over the Dodgers.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He became the fourth major leaguer to hit his 100th home run in his third season, along with Ralph Kiner, Eddie Mathews and Joe DiMaggio.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit his 114th home run on September 20 in a game against the Astros, which tied him with Kiner for the most home runs by a player in his first three seasons.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In 157 games, Pujols hit 43 home runs (fourth in the league, behind Jim Thome, Richie Sexson and Bonds) and had 124 RBI's (tied with Sexson for fourth and behind Preston Wilson, Gary Sheffield and Thome).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He became the youngest player since Tommy Davis in 1962 to win the NL batting title after batting .359, and he led the league in runs (137), hits (212), and doubles (51).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols joined Rogers Hornsby as the only players in the Cardinals' history to record more than 40 homers and 200 hits in the same season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Though his stellar play had Cardinals' fans chanting "M-V-P!" during home games as early as June, Pujols again finished second to Bonds in MVP voting.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He won his second Silver Slugger Award and first *Sporting News* Player of the Year Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols' contributions helped the Cardinals rank second in batting average and third in home runs in the NL; however, the pitching staff posted a 4.60 ERA, which was below the league average, and the Cardinals missed the playoffs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] After receiving many awards in his first three seasons, Pujols was rewarded monetarily for his accomplishments on February 20, 2004, when he signed a seven-year, $100 million contract extension with a $16 million club option for 2011 with no-trade provisions.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was moved to first base in 2004 after the Cardinals traded Tino Martinez in the offseason.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On June 16, he hit a walk-off home run against Reds pitcher Mike Matthews in the 10th inning of a 4–3 victory.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols' highlights later in the season included a July game in which he hit five RBI and three home runs in a thrilling win over the rival Chicago Cubs, and another in which he broke up a no-hitter by Giants pitcher Dustin Hermanson.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] During a September game against the Rockies, he earned his 500th RBI, joining Joe DiMaggio and Ted Williams as the only players to have 500 RBI in their first four seasons.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He also led the league with 133 runs scored.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On defense, he tied for the league lead in errors by a first baseman, with 14.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He finished third in MVP voting (behind Bonds and Beltré), joining Musial as the only Cardinals to finish in the top five in voting for at least four years in a row.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He won the Silver Slugger Award at first base, the third position he won the award at.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols, along with teammates Edmonds and Rolen, earned the nickname "MV3" for their phenomenal seasons; Pujols led the three in home runs and batting average.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals won the NL Central, aided by pitcher Chris Carpenter, who won 15 games and had a 3.46 ERA his first season with the team en route to winning the National League Comeback Player of the Year Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 4 of the NLDS against the Dodgers, Pujols hit a three-run home run against Wilson Álvarez and had four RBI as the Cardinals won, 6–2, and took the series three games to one.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 6 of the NLCS, Pujols had three hits, scored three runs (including the winning run), and hit a two-run home run off Munro in a 12-inning, 6–4 victory.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals won the series in seven games, advancing to the World Series for the first time since 1987.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols was named the NLCS MVP after batting .500 with four home runs and nine RBI.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was one of three Cardinals batters hit over .250 in the series against the Boston Red Sox, batting .333 as the Cardinals were swept by Boston in four games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] By 2005, many baseball fans thought that Pujols was the best Cardinal since Musial.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols picked up his 100th RBI of the season on August 31, joining Williams, DiMaggio and Al Simmons as the only players with 100 RBI in their first five seasons.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit his 200th career home run in a game against the Reds on September 30, making him the third-youngest major league player to reach that milestone (behind Mel Ott and Eddie Mathews) and the second-fastest to reach it (behind Kiner).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] For the first time in his career, he won the NL MVP award as Bonds was limited to 14 games due to an injury.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols returned to the playoffs as the Cardinals won the NL Central for the second year in a row.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had five hits in nine at-bats with four runs scored and two RBI in the NLDS as the Cardinals swept the Padres.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 5 of the NLCS against the Astros, with the Cardinals trailing by two runs and only one out from elimination in the ninth inning, Pujols hit a game-winning three-run home run against Brad Lidge that landed on the train tracks in the back of Minute Maid Park.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] *MLB.com* writer Matthew Leach later called it "one of the most famous playoff home runs in recent years." Nevertheless, the Cardinals were eliminated in Game 6 by the Astros.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols batted .304 with two home runs and six RBI in the series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Over two games in April 2006, Pujols hit home runs in four consecutive plate appearances, making him the 20th player to accomplish the feat.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols maintained after the game that he was more concerned with winning than the numbers: "I don't look at numbers," he said.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] I didn't know anything about [the record] until you guys brought it up.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] I don't get locked in on anything like that.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] I get locked in on seeing the ball and helping my team out to win and hopefully doing some damage out there." Pujols had three hits and four RBI, including his 1,000th career hit (a home run against Jerome Williams), as the Cardinals defeated the Cubs 9–3 on April 21, 2006.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On June 4, he was placed on the disabled list (DL) for the first time in his career with a strained right oblique that kept him out for three weeks.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On August 22, Pujols hit a three-run home run and a grand slam against John Maine in an 8–7 loss to the Mets.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On September 28, with the Cardinals trailing the Padres 2–1 in the eighth inning, he hit a three-run home run against Cla Meredith, helping the Cardinals win 4–2 and end a seven-game losing streak.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished the season with a .331 average (third to Freddy Sanchez's .344 and Cabrera's .339), 177 hits, 33 doubles, 49 home runs (second to Ryan Howard's 58), 137 RBI (second to Howard, 149) and 119 runs scored (tied with Matt Holliday, Hanley Ramírez, and Alfonso Soriano for fifth).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Of his 49 home runs, 20 produced a game-winning RBI, breaking Willie Mays' single-season record set in 1962.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He finished second to Howard in MVP voting and won the NL Gold Glove Award for first base.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He won his first of four consecutive Fielding Bible Awards for the first base position.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Led by Pujols and Carpenter, the Cardinals won the NL Central and reached the playoffs for the third year in a row.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 1 of the NLDS against the Padres, he hit a game-winning two-run home run against Jake Peavy as the Cardinals won 5–1.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had a game-winning RBI against David Wells and had three hits in Game 2 as the Cardinals won 2–0.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .333 with a home run and an RBI in the series as the Cardinals defeated the Padres in four games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 2 of the NLCS against the Mets, Pujols scored three runs as the Cardinals won 9–6.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .318 with one home run and one RBI in the series as the Cardinals defeated the Mets in seven games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 1 of the World Series against the Detroit Tigers, he hit a two-run home run against Justin Verlander as the Cardinals won 7–2.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 5, he made a sprawling, flip-from-his-back play to rob Plácido Polanco of a hit as the Cardinals clinched the series, giving Pujols his first career World Series ring.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Near the beginning of the 2007 season in an April 22 game against the Cubs, Pujols hit a game-winning three-run home run against Ryan Dempster in the 10th inning of a 12–9 victory, tying Ken Boyer for second all-time on the Cardinals' home run list with his 255th.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished the season with 185 hits, 38 doubles and 103 RBI (a career-low).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was among the league leaders in batting average (.327, sixth) and home runs (32, tied for tenth).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He scored 99 runs, ending his streak of seasons with at least 30 home runs, a .300 average, 100 runs scored and 100 RBI, at six.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He grounded into a major-league-leading 27 double plays.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He finished ninth in MVP voting, the first year he had finished outside the top five.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols began 2008 by reaching base in 42 straight games, the longest streak to open a season since 1999.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On June 11, he was placed on the 15-day disabled list with a strained left calf muscle.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit his 300th home run against Bob Howry on July 4 in a 2–1 loss to the Cubs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He said after the game that to him it was "just another homer that goes out of the park.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He regretted that the milestone came in a loss, saying, "I wish it would have come with a great win.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He grounded into a National League-leading 27 double plays.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols won his second NL MVP Award, and he won the Silver Slugger Award for the fourth time in his career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was named *The Sporting News* Player of the Year for the second time in his career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] For his work off the field, he was named the 2008 winner of the Roberto Clemente Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He considered having Tommy John surgery after the season but underwent nerve transposition surgery on his right elbow instead to ease discomfort.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On April 25, 2009, Pujols picked up his 1,000th career RBI with a 441-foot grand slam against David Patton in an 8–2 victory over the Cubs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] "I hit that ball as good as I can hit a ball," he said after the game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On July 3, he hit his 10th career grand slam against Weathers in a 7–4 victory over the Reds, breaking Musial's record for most grand slams by a Cardinal.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The grand slam was also his 350th career home run, making him the third-fastest player to reach the milestone, behind Alex Rodriguez and Ken Griffey Jr.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He received the highest number of votes in NL history for the All-Star Game that year.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols had four hits, scored three runs, and knocked in five RBI on August 4, including a grand slam against Sean Green that tied the NL record for most grand slams in a season (five), in a 10-inning, 12–7 victory over the Mets.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In 160 games, Pujols batted .327 (third, behind Ramírez's .342 and Pablo Sandoval's .330) with 186 hits (sixth), 45 doubles (second to Miguel Tejada's 46), 47 home runs (first), 135 RBI (third behind Fielder and Howard's 141) and 124 runs scored (first).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was unanimously named the NL MVP for the third time, tying Musial as the Cardinals' leader in that category.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] For the fifth time in his career, he won the Silver Slugger Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He won the *Sporting News* MLB Player of the Year award for the second consecutive year, joining Williams and Joe Morgan as the only players to win it in back-to-back years.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] For the fourth year in a row, he won the Fielding Bible Award for first base.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Aided by the mid-season acquisition of Matt Holliday (who replaced Ryan Ludwick as the cleanup hitter) and the emergence of Adam Wainwright (who led the NL in wins), the Cardinals returned to the playoffs after a two-year hiatus.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In the NLDS against the Dodgers, Pujols batted .300 with one RBI as the Cardinals were swept in three games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Following the postseason, Pujols had surgery to remove five bone spurs from his right elbow.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals called the surgery a "success", and Dr.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] James Andrews decided that Pujols did not need Tommy John surgery.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] For April 2010, Pujols earned his first Pepsi Clutch Performer of the Month Award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .348, 1.270 OPS, three home runs and 14 RBI with runners on base.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Further, in situations with his team leading by one run, tied, or having the potential tying run on base, at bat, or on deck after the seventh inning ("late-and-close"), he batted .583 (7-for-12) with a home run, two doubles, three RBI and five runs scored.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On June 29, in an 8–0 victory over the Diamondbacks, Pujols hit five RBI and hit two home runs against Dontrelle Willis for his 37th career multi-homer game, which tied Musial's franchise record for multi-homer games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] "It's pretty special," he said of tying Musial.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] "I'm blessed to have the opportunity to be compared sometimes with him." On August 26, he hit his 400th career home run against Jordan Zimmermann in a 13-inning, 11–10 loss to the Nationals.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He became the third-youngest player to reach the milestone – behind Griffey Jr. and Rodriguez – and he became the fourth-quickest player by at bats to reach the milestone (behind McGwire, Babe Ruth, Harmon Killebrew, and Thome).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On September 11, in a 12-inning 6–3 loss to Atlanta, Pujols had three RBI and reached 100 RBI for the 10th consecutive year with a two-run double against Tommy Hanson.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Only Al Simmons has a longer streak of 100 RBI seasons at the beginning of a career, with 11.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols joined Jimmie Foxx, Lou Gehrig, and Rodriguez in having 10 consecutive seasons of 100 or more RBI at any time in their career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Foxx and Rodriguez are the only two players besides Pujols to have 10 consecutive years of 30 home runs and 100 RBI.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The next day, in a 7–3 victory over the Braves, he passed Musial to be the all-time Cardinals' leader in multi-home run games when he hit two home runs against Tim Hudson for the 38th time in a game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In 159 games, Pujols batted .312 (sixth) with 183 hits (fifth) and 39 doubles (tied for eighth with Marlon Byrd); he led the league in runs scored (115), home runs (42) and RBI (118).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He won his second Gold Glove Award for first base, and he won the NL First Base Silver Slugger Award for the sixth time.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He finished second in the NL MVP voting to Joey Votto, who said he was "shocked" that Pujols only got one first-place vote.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols and the Cardinals set a deadline for the start of 2011 spring training for contract extension negotiations but failed to reach an agreement.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] After Pujols struggled in his first 30 games of the season in batting .231, he batted .316 with 30 home runs in his final 117 games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Against the Cubs, he hit consecutive extra-inning walk-off home runs on June 4 and 5 for the first time since Albert Belle in 1995.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Carpenter noted after the game that Pujols' slump earlier in the year was over: "He continues to do great things, there's no doubt about it," he said.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] "The things that he's done the last few days have been just like the old Albert." On June 19 against the Royals, Wilson Betemit collided with Pujols, inducing a small fracture his left wrist and keeping him inactive until July 5.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On July 30, in a 9–2 victory over the Cubs, he got his 2,000th career hit against Carlos Mármol, becoming the fifth Cardinal to reach 2,000 hits and 12th-fastest major leaguer by games to reach the milestone.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In the Cardinals' final game of the season, against the Astros on September 28, he had the game-winning RBI against Brett Myers in the 8–0 victory, helping the Cardinals overcome a 10.5-game deficit to Atlanta to win the Wild Card.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished the season with 173 hits (tied for ninth with Aramis Ramírez), 29 doubles (a career-low), and 105 runs scored (tied for third with Justin Upton behind Ryan Braun's 109 and Matt Kemp's 115).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 2 of the NLDS against the Phillies on October 2, Pujols had a game-winning RBI single against Cliff Lee in the 5–4 victory.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .350 with one RBI in the series as the Cardinals defeated the Phillies in five games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 2 of the NLCS against the Brewers, he had four hits, three runs scored, one home run and five RBI, in a 12–3 victory.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He batted .478 with two home runs and nine RBI in the series as the Cardinals defeated the Brewers in six games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On October 22, in Game 3 of the World Series, Pujols had five hits, three home runs, four runs scored and six RBI in a 16–7 victory over the Rangers.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had one hit and no RBI the other six games of the series but became a World Series champion for the second time as the Cardinals defeated the Rangers in seven games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] After the season, he became a free agent for the first time in his career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Three teams were reported to be interested in Pujols during the 2011 offseason: the Cardinals, the Miami Marlins, and the Los Angeles Angels.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals offered Pujols a 10-year, $210 million deal (with $30 million deferred), but Pujols rejected it.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] His wife, Deidre, explained on a radio talk show that they were "insulted" and "confused" that the Cardinals had initially offered Pujols a five-year deal.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Marlins reportedly offered Pujols a 10-year contract too, but on December 8, he signed a 10-year deal with the Angels worth around $254 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols did not perform very well to begin the 2012 season, batting .217 with no home runs and four RBI in the month of April.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Soon after the Angels called up top prospect Mike Trout and fired hitting coach Mickey Hatcher, Pujols' numbers began to rise, as he batted .323 with 13 home runs from May 15 through the All-Star Break.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On July 31, he hit two home runs against Derek Holland in a 6–2 victory over the Rangers.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] After the game, Holland observed that Pujols had "definitely turned it around, no doubt about it...
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had a slow start, but he's picked it up.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He's a great hitter...." On August 14, Pujols had four RBIs, including a game-winning three-run home run against Ubaldo Jiménez in a 9–6 victory over the Cleveland Indians.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In 2012, Pujols batted .285 (at the time, a career low) in 153 games with 173 hits, 50 doubles (second to Alex Gordon's 51), 30 home runs, 105 RBIs (7th in AL), and 85 runs scored.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In 2013, Pujols had by far the worst season of his career to date, failing to play at least 100 games in a season for the first time.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols also posted career worsts in hits, runs scored, doubles, home runs, RBI, walks, batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage, and OPS.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Overall in 99 games, Pujols batted .258 with 101 hits, 19 doubles, 17 home runs, 64 RBI, and 49 runs scored.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On August 19, 2013, Pujols was ruled out for the remainder of the 2013 season after suffering a foot injury.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Louis WGNU radio show, former Cardinals player Jack Clark accused Pujols of having used performance-enhancing drugs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Clark served as the Cardinals' hitting coach during the early part of Pujols' tenure in St.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On the morning of August 9, Pujols issued a statement adamantly denying that he had ever taken PEDs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He denounced Clark's allegations as "irresponsible and reckless," and threatened to sue Clark and WGNU over the allegations.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Partly due to legal threats from Pujols, InsideSTL Enterprises, which owns WGNU's weekday airtime under a time brokerage agreement, cut ties with Clark.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On October 4, 2013, Pujols filed a defamation lawsuit against Clark.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In response, Clark challenged Pujols, proposing that they both take polygraph tests to resolve who is telling the truth.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] However, on February 10, 2014, Clark apologized and retracted his accusations against Pujols, saying he had "no knowledge whatsoever" that Pujols ever used PEDs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] "During a heated discussion on air, I misspoke," Clark said.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On April 22, 2014, Pujols hit his 499th and 500th home runs off the Washington Nationals' Taylor Jordan at Nationals Park, where he had hit his 400th career home run in the 2010 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols became the 26th player ever to reach the 500-home-run mark, the third-youngest to reach it, and the only player to hit Nos.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On August 10, he played in MLB's longest game of the year, and the longest in the history of Angel Stadium, ending the 19-inning, 6-hours-and-31-minute contest against the Red Sox with a solo home run for a 5–4 final score.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] It was his first walk-off home run as an Angel and first since June 2011.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On September 6, against the Minnesota Twins, Pujols collected his 2,500th career hit, a two-run go-ahead double off of Jared Burton in the 9th inning.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He also passed the 1,500-run mark in the same game.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In the process, he became the fifth player in major league history with 2,500 hits and 500 home runs while maintaining a .310 lifetime batting average, after Babe Ruth, Jimmie Foxx, Ted Williams and Manny Ramirez.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] For the 2014 season, Pujols batted .272 and grounded into an American League-leading 28 double plays.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was tied for the 3rd-highest salary in the AL, at $23 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] After the 2014 season, Pujols traveled to Japan to join a team of MLB All-Stars playing against the All-Stars of Nippon Professional Baseball in the Japan All-Star Series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Before the 2015 season, Pujols enjoyed his first offseason in his time with the Angels in which he was both free of injury or recuperation from injury.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] However, his offensive production lagged behind his career levels the first month of the season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] By the end of April, Pujols was batting .208 with three home runs and nine RBI in 86 plate appearances.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The next month, Pujols' offensive production had started to come around.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Between May 28 and June 22, he batted .356 with 15 homers, 30 RBI, and a 1.326 OPS.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] At this time, he was leading the American League in home runs with 23.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] After batting .303/.395/.737 with 13 home runs in June 2015, Pujols was named AL Player of the Month for the first time and seventh overall monthly award.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] His home run total led the major leagues and 73 total bases tied Manny Machado for first in the AL.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Remarkably, his batting average on balls in play was .218, significantly lower than the league average of about .300.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Selected to the All Star Game, Pujols was announced as a reserve for the American League.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Due to an injury just days earlier with Tigers slugger Miguel Cabrera, Pujols instead started at first base.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] It was his 10th overall selection to the midsummer classic, and first as a member of the Angels.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On September 22, Pujols hit his 556th career home run to pass Ramírez for sole possession of 14th place on the all-time career home run leaderboard.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In the last game of the season, on October 4, Pujols hit his 40th home run, the seventh time he had done so in a season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Among active MLB players, he trailed only Alex Rodriguez, with eight.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] With Trout also hitting 40 home runs, the 2015 Angels became just the 31st team in MLB history with multiple players to hit 40+ home runs in a season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] For the 2015 season, he batted .244/.307/.480, and he had the lowest batting average on balls in play (.217) of all major league players.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was tied for the 3rd-highest salary in the AL, at $24 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On April 30, 2016, Pujols became the 85th player to make 10,000 career plate appearances.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On May 2, Pujols became the 20th player all-time to amass 5,000 career total bases.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On August 17, Pujols joined Barry Bonds as the only other player to be intentionally walked over 300 times.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Playing the Toronto Blue Jays on August 25, he reached 100 RBI for the 13th time in his career, the fifth player to do so.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] While playing Cincinnati on August 29, Pujols hit his 26th home run and 103rd RBI of the season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The home run tied him with Frank Robinson for ninth place on the all-time home run list at 586, and allowed him to become the seventh player all-time with 1,200 career extra base hits, and the 21st to reach 1,800 RBI.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On September 16, Pujols became the 16th player all-time to reach 600 career doubles.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He tied for 2nd in the AL in double plays grounded into, with 24.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had the 6th-highest salary in the league, at $25 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On June 3, 2017, Pujols became the ninth player in Major League history to hit at least 600 home runs, when he hit a grand slam off of Ervin Santana of the Minnesota Twins.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was the fourth-youngest player to achieve the feat (behind Alex Rodriguez, Babe Ruth and Hank Aaron), and the first to hit a grand slam for his 600th home run.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] For the 2017 season, Pujols played in 149 games and had 593 at bats, but set career-lows in batting average (.241), on base percentage (.286), slugging percentage (.386), doubles (17), and walks (37), while leading the majors by grounding into 26 double plays.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had the slowest baserunning sprint speed of all major league players, at 21.8 feet/second.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had the 6th-highest salary in the AL, at $26 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On May 4, 2018, Pujols recorded his 3,000th major league hit, against Mike Leake of the Seattle Mariners.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On July 12, Pujols hit his 630th career home run, moving into a tie with Ken Griffey Jr. for sixth place all-time for that category.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The next day, Pujols was placed on the 10-day disabled list due to left knee inflammation.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He hit a single on August 10 for his 1,000th hit as an Angel, becoming the ninth player to record 1,000 hits in both the American League and National League.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had surgery on his left knee in August, ending his season, and on his right elbow to remove a bone spur in September.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In 2018, he batted .245/.289/.411 with 19 home runs and 64 RBIs (matching the lowest season total of his career).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had the slowest baserunning sprint speed of all major league players for the second consecutive year, at 22.2 feet/second.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was the sixth-oldest player in the American League.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had the 5th-highest salary in the AL, at $27 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On May 9, 2019, Pujols became the fourth player in major league history to record 2,000 RBIs, hitting a solo home run against the Detroit Tigers at Comerica Park.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] A Tigers fan caught the 2,000 RBI ball but refused to turn it over to MLB officials, saying that he wanted to sleep on it before making a decision.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In response, MLB refused to authenticate the ball.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The fan, Ely Hydes, eventually decided that he wanted to return the ball to Pujols, who in turn refused, stating that the fan should either keep the ball or donate it to the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols hit his 200th home run as an Angel on June 13, becoming only the sixth player to hit 200 home runs with two different teams.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols had the lowest line drive percentage of all major league hitters (15.3%), and the 16.7% of balls he hit to the opposite field were the lowest in baseball.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had the second-slowest sprint speed of all major league players, at 22.5 feet/second.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was the third-oldest player in the American League, behind Ichiro Suzuki (who retired in March) and Fernando Rodney.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was tied for the 4th-highest salary in the AL, at $28 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] At the beginning of the 2020 season, Pujols (at the age of 40) was the oldest player in the major leagues.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On August 24, Pujols passed Rodriguez to reach second on the all-time RBIs list with a single against the Astros.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] With his 2,087th RBI, he trailed only Hank Aaron's 2,297.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] (Babe Ruth has 2,214 RBIs as recognized by Baseball Reference, but only 1,989 on the official MLB list; MLB does not count pre-1920 RBIs because it was not yet an official statistic.) On September 18, Pujols hit his 661st career home run to pass Willie Mays for fifth place all-time.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He had the slowest sprint speed of all major league players, at 22.0 feet/second.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was tied for the 7th-highest salary in the league, at $29 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols began the 2021 season with the Angels.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On May 6, 2021, the Angels designated Pujols for assignment.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Through 24 games, Pujols was hitting .198/.250/.372 with five home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On May 13, Pujols cleared waivers and became a free agent.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In nine-plus seasons with the Angels, Pujols hit .256 with 222 homers and 783 runs batted in.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] During his time with the Angels, the team won the AL West once (in 2014) and won no postseason games.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In 2016, sportswriter Joe Posnanski of NBC Sports described Pujols as "a cautionary tale against big contracts" and "an overpaid designated hitter in the middle of the lineup for a going-nowhere Los Angeles Angels team".
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On May 17, 2021, Pujols agreed to a one-year major league deal with the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He made his Dodgers debut that night as the starting first baseman against the Arizona Diamondbacks.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] With his longtime number 5 having been assigned to Corey Seager, Pujols chose the number 55; both as nods to his two former teams, as well as the Bible.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] "If you know the Bible," Pujols explained, "it's the number of grace.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] So I feel 5-5, double grace." On May 20, Pujols hit his first home run as a Dodger, a two-run homer off Merrill Kelly of the Diamondbacks.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In October, Scott Miller of *The New York Times* asserted that Pujols had "flourished beyond expectations, scorching lefties for a .306 batting average".
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Overall, in 2021 he appeared in 85 games for the Dodgers and hit .254 with a .299 on base percentage, 12 homers, and 38 RBIs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] For the second season in a row, he had the slowest baserunning sprint speed of all major league players, at 22.4 feet/second.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] His line drive percentage of 15.4% was the lowest in the major leagues, and his 16.7% of balls hit to the opposite field was the lowest in the majors.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was the oldest player in the league for the second season in a row, and had the fifth-highest salary at $30 million.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In his first postseason appearance since 2014, he appeared in nine games for the Dodgers, with five hits in 18 at bats for a batting average of .278.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols subsequently announced that he would play in the Dominican Professional Baseball League (LIDOM) in the offseason, for Leones del Escogido.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On March 28, 2022, Pujols signed a one-year contract to return to the St.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Louis Cardinals and announced that 2022 would be his final season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He said, "There were a lot of teams interested.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] It took 12 hours, maybe even less, to get a deal done once we received a call from the Cardinals," adding: "We have the best fans in baseball.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] It feels like I never left." He was the oldest player in the major leagues for the third season in a row.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On May 15, Pujols made his pitching debut, the oldest player to do so since 1929.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In a 15–6 blowout win against the San Francisco Giants, he gave up two home runs and four earned runs in the ninth inning.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On June 4 against the Chicago Cubs, he became the 10th major league player to play 3,000 games, appearing as an injury replacement for Corey Dickerson.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On June 7 against the Tampa Bay Rays, Pujols singled for his 3,320th career hit, passing Paul Molitor for tenth all-time in hits.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On July 10, after the Philadelphia Phillies had shut out the Cardinals in three straight games, Pujols made a rare start against a right-handed pitcher, and his three hits, including a home run, helped spark a 4–3 win.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The home run was Pujols' 1,377th extra-base hit, tying him for third all-time with Stan Musial.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols was chosen to be on the National League team for the All-Star Game by MLB Commissioner Rob Manfred as a "legacy" selection to honor his career achievements.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was also selected to participate in the Home Run Derby, where he advanced to the second round and fell one home run short of eventual winner Juan Soto.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On August 20, he passed Musial for second place all-time in total bases, trailing only Hank Aaron.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols became the first player to produce four hits and two homers in a single game at age 42 or older and was named the National League Player of the Week (alongside teammate Paul Goldschmidt) after hitting .615 with three home runs and seven RBIs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On August 29, Pujols hit a third-inning home run off of Ross Detwiler, the 450th unique pitcher to surrender a home run to Pujols, breaking another MLB record.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On September 10 and 11, Pujols hit his 696th and 697th home runs, at PNC Park against the Pittsburgh Pirates, to move into fourth place on the all-time list.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On September 14, he became the second player in MLB history to officially compile 2,200 RBIs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols on hitting his 700th home run in Los Angeles.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On September 23, Pujols became the fourth player to hit 700 career home runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] His 699th and 700th home runs came during consecutive at-bats during an 11–0 victory for the Cardinals at Dodger Stadium.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] 699 off Andrew Heaney, his 200th home run off a left-handed pitcher; and his 700th off Phil Bickford, his 500th home run off a right-handed pitcher.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] 702 in his last career home game, mirroring the home run he hit in his St.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] 703, which gave him undisputed possession of second place on the all-time RBI list, surpassing Babe Ruth's unofficial total.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Pujols finished his regular-season career first in double plays grounded into (426), third in sacrifice flies (123), fifth in games played (3,080) and doubles (686), and sixth in at bats (11,421).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] After the season was finished, Pujols was named National League Comeback Player of the Year.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Cardinals won the National League Central division, earning a berth in the postseason and enabling Pujols' 10th and final postseason appearance.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He went 2-for-8 in the National League Wild Card Series against the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In Game 2 on October 8, he singled in his last two at-bats.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Phillies won the game, eliminating the Cardinals and bringing Pujols' playing career to an end.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On November 1, it was announced that Pujols had signed retirement papers with the Cardinals.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On February 23, 2023, the Angels hired Pujols as a special assistant as part of a 10–year personal services contract.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Since retiring, Pujols has also been an analyst on MLB Network.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In June 2023, Pujols was named the "official global ambassador" of Baseball United, a professional baseball organization in the Middle East and South Asia.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] He was also reported to have an ownership interest in the league.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] After his playing career, Pujols has also been involved in the managerial side of things, a rarity for all-time greats.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] In February 2024, Pujols was named the manager of the Leones del Escogido.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] The Leones del Escogido won the Serie Final of the 2024–25 season and the 2025 Caribbean Series.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] Ramón Santiago was hired to replace Pujols for the 2025–26 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p01] On December 28, 2025, the Estrellas Orientales announced that Pujols would be their manager for the 2026–27 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols' swing was praised for its consistency.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] "It's the same swing every time," former teammate Lance Berkman once said.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] "He has the ability to repeat his swing over and over and over, which leads to him being very consistent," Cardinals' video coordinator Chad Blair said.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Habib described the swing as "quick" and "quiet".
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols used a 32.5-ounce bat against right-handed pitchers, but used a 33-ounce bat against left-handers to avoid trying to pull the ball when he swung.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols is second in major league history in runs batted in and total bases behind only Hank Aaron.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] He and Aaron are the only two players to amass 3,000 hits, 700 home runs, and 2,200 RBIs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Only two other players (Stan Musial and Willie Mays) have surpassed 6,000 total bases.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols hit home runs off of a record 458 different pitchers over the course of his career, and is fourth in career home runs and fifth in doubles.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] In 2009, Pujols set the major league single-season record for assists by a first baseman with 185.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] In an age when seasons of 150+ strikeouts were the norm for sluggers, he never struck out 100 times in a season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols earned uncommonly high praise from players and coaches throughout his career.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] In 2008, he was named the most feared hitter in baseball in a poll of all 30 MLB managers.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Given his career achievements, Pujols is widely expected to be inducted into the Hall of Fame and potentially a unanimous selection the first year in which he becomes eligible (2028).
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] In 2006, Pujols and the Hanon family opened Pujols 5 Westport Grill, a restaurant located in Westport Plaza of Maryland Heights, Missouri.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] A 10-foot, 1,100-lb. statue of Pujols was dedicated on November 2, 2011, outside the restaurant.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] An anonymous donor commissioned sculptor Harry Weber to create the statue, which belongs to the Pujols Family Foundation.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] After Pujols signed with the Angels, the restaurant was renamed the St.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Louis Soccer United, a group looking to bring a Major League Soccer (MLS) franchise to the St.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] However, the group's bid for a franchise was unsuccessful, and a USL team (Saint Louis FC) was formed.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Among other activities, the foundation hosts events for people with Down syndrome.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] The foundation gave the Down Syndrome Association of Greater St.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Louis the resources to open an office and hire staff.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] In 2009, the Albert Pujols Wellness Center for Adults with Down Syndrome opened in Chesterfield, Missouri; Pujols was present at the opening on November 18.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] The foundation hosts an annual "All Stars Basketball Game" with down syndrome players at Missouri Baptist University.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols has been a part of several medical missions to the Dominican Republic, by taking supplies as well as supporting doctors and dentists for those in need medical care.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] The Pujols Family Foundation also holds an annual golf tournament to raise money to send dentists to the Dominican Republic.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] In 2009, Pujols donated money to the Mike Coolbaugh Memorial Tournament, allowing the event to occur after a sponsor backed out.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] On August 28, 2010, Pujols and La Russa attended Glenn Beck's "Restoring Honor" rally in Washington, D.C., after being assured by Beck that the rally was not political.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] During the rally, Pujols was presented with a medal for his off-the-field efforts.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols married Deidre Pujols on January 1, 2000.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] He filed for divorce on April 4, 2022, after 22 years of marriage, citing irreconcilable differences.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols is a devout evangelical Christian.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] He became an evangelical Christian on November 13, 1998, influenced in part by Deidre and his grandmother.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] During his first tenure with the Cardinals, Pujols and his family attended West County Community Church, a Southern Baptist church in Wildwood, Missouri.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] On September 2, 2023, Pujols married Nicole Fernandez, the daughter of former President of the Dominican Republic, Leonel Fernández.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] The two had been dating since September 2022, shortly before Pujols’ playing career ended.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] During his playing days, even with the Angels and Dodgers, Pujols lived in St.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] He owned a home in Irvine, California, but put it up for sale in 2016.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols is a supporter of people with Down syndrome, a condition his daughter Isabella was born with.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] In 2007, Pujols became a U.S. citizen, scoring a perfect 100 on his citizenship test.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols is close friends with third baseman Plácido Polanco, a former teammate with the Cardinals.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Polanco has called Pujols his "closest friend in baseball", and Pujols is the godfather to Polanco's son, Ishmael.
[src:batting-order-baseball/albert-pujols-p02] Pujols is also friends with Robinson Canó, who selected Pujols' Angels teammate Mark Trumbo for the 2012 Home Run Derby after being asked to by Pujols.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In baseball, the **batting order** or **batting lineup** is the sequence in which the members of the offense take their turns in batting against the pitcher.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The batting order is the main component of a team's offensive strategy.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In Major League Baseball, the batting order is set by the manager, who before the game begins must present the home plate umpire with two copies of his team's **lineup card**, a card on which a team's starting batting order is recorded.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The home plate umpire keeps one copy of the lineup card of each team, and gives the second copy to the opposing manager.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Once the home plate umpire gives the lineup cards to the opposing managers, the batting lineup is final and a manager can make changes only under the Official Baseball Rules governing substitutions.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] If a team bats out of order, it is a violation of baseball's rules and subject to penalty.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] According to *The Dickson Baseball Dictionary*, a team has "batted around" when each of the nine batters in the team's lineup has made a plate appearance, and the first batter is coming up again during a single inning.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Dictionary.com, however, defines "bat around" as "to have every player in the lineup take a turn at bat during a single inning." It is not an official statistic.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Opinions differ as to whether nine batters must get an at-bat, or if the opening batter must bat again for "batting around" to have occurred.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In modern American baseball, some batting positions have nicknames: "leadoff" for first, "cleanup" for fourth, and "last" for ninth.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Others are known by the ordinal numbers or the term #-hole (3rd place hitter would be 3-hole).
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] At the start of each inning, the batting order resumes where it left off in the previous inning; it does not reset to start with the #1 hitter again.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] If the current batter did not finish his at-bat during the previous inning (because another baserunner becomes the third out, by being picked-off or caught stealing), he will lead off the next inning with the pitch count reset to 0-0.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Early forms of baseball or rounders from the mid 19th century did not require a fixed batting order; any player who was not on base could be called upon to bat.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The concept of a set batting order is said to have been invented by Alexander Cartwright, who also instituted rules such as the foul ball and tagging the runner (as opposed to pegging him with the ball), and devised the shortstop position.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the rules did not require that the batting order be announced before game time.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] This permitted strategic decisions regarding batting order to occur while the game was in progress.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] For example, Cap Anson was known to wait to see if the first two men got on base in the first inning.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] If they did not, he would wait and hit in the next inning.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] However, in the 1880s, organized baseball began mandating that the batting order be disclosed before the first pitch.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In cricket, the batting order is generally fixed so that players are sure of their role within the team, but there is no obligation to submit a definitive batting order and stick to it.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] A *batsman* can be "promoted" to a higher spot (or conversely, demoted to a lower one) in the batting order according to the team's wishes.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In the shorter form of cricket, there is only one innings per side, while in the longer form each side bats a maximum of two times.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In a typical innings of this latter form, all eleven players on the team will have a chance to bat, and the innings finishes when 10 players are out.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In the team's second innings, the batting order is usually maintained, but the team can make any changes it desires.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] However, it should also be remembered that in cricket a single innings lasts hours or even days, and there are periods in which batting can be markedly easier or more difficult.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] A related factor is that a single ball is used in an innings for around 80 overs (approximately 5 hours of play).
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] At the beginning of an innings, therefore, when bowlers are fresh and the ball is hard, it would be appreciably more challenging for the non-specialist batsmen to make an impact.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Conversely, if such a player bats when the ball is old and the bowlers are tired, he can thrive, and this can often be a great source of pleasure to spectators, as insult is added to injury for the other side.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Finally, in cricket, there is no such thing as a designated hitter, so even if a bowler has no batting ability, he will still be required to bat, usually as the last man in the order.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The first player in the batting order is known as the leadoff hitter.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The leadoff batter is traditionally an individual with a high on-base percentage, plate discipline, bat control, good speed, and the ability to steal bases.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] His goal is to ensure the team has baserunners when the later, more powerful hitters come to bat.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Once on base, his main goal is to get into scoring position (that is, 2nd or 3rd base) as quickly as possible, either through steals, hit and run plays or intelligent baserunning decisions, and then on to score.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] His need for a high on-base percentage (OBP) exceeds that of the other lineup spots.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Because leadoff hitters are selected primarily for their speed and ability to reach base, they are typically not power hitters, but contact hitters.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Leadoff hitters typically hit mostly singles and doubles and draw walks to get on base.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Although speed is not essential, as was shown by Wade Boggs, it is highly desired among leadoff hitters.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] However, today's model for a leadoff hitter developed only gradually.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The term “leadoff hitter” can be used interchangeably to describe not only the first batter on the lineup card, but also the first batter up in any particular inning.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] For example, if, in the second inning, the fifth batter in the lineup card is the first batter up, it will be said that he is leading off or that he is the leadoff batter for that particular inning.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The second batter is usually a contact hitter with the ability to bunt or sacrifice a baserunner over or get a hit.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] His main goal is to move the leadoff man into scoring position and to avoid grounding into double plays.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Managers often like to have a left-handed hitter bat second because of the potential gap in the infield defense caused by the first baseman holding the leadoff batter.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] As early as 1892, it was recognized that a left-handed hitter in the second spot would make it easier for a man on base to steal second.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The third batter, in the *three-hole*, is generally the best all-around hitter on the team, often hitting for a high batting average but not necessarily very fast.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Part of his job is to reach base for the cleanup hitter, and part of it is to help drive in baserunners himself.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Third-place hitters are best known for "keeping the inning alive".
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] However, in recent years, some managers have tended to put their best slugger in this position.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The fourth player in the batting order is known as the cleanup hitter, also known as the *cleanup spot* and in modern baseball is almost always one of the best hitters on the team, often the one with the most power and ability to drive in runs with extra-base hits (double, triple, or home run).
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Baseball managers tend to place hitters who are most likely to reach base ahead of the clean-up man, so that the fourth batter can "clean" the bases by driving these baserunners home to score runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] His main goal is to drive in runs, although he is expected to score runs as well.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Hitting cleanup requires an exceptional level of talent, and the ability to deliver big hits in important situations (such as the bases loaded with two out).
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Examples of #4 hitters include Edgar Martínez, Lou Gehrig, Joe DiMaggio, Eddie Mathews, Norm Cash, Willie McCovey, Billy Williams, Tony Pérez, Fred McGriff, Eddie Murray, Daniel Murphy, Alex Rodriguez, Prince Fielder, David Ortiz, and Ryan Howard.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The theory behind the cleanup hitter is that, at the beginning of the game, if at least one of the first three batters reaches base with a single-base hit or walk, a home run will result in two or more runs rather than just one (a "solo" home run).
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] If all three players reach base, thereby loading the bases, the cleanup hitter has the chance to hit a grand slam, scoring four runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] But even without the grand slam, this batter can extend an inning with a high batting average and frequent walks.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] However, since home runs were a rarity before 1920, the concept of slotting a home run hitter fourth was slow to develop.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Regardless, the need for a good run producer in that position was recognized from the early days in baseball history, as demonstrated by player-manager Cap Anson generally penciling his name there.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] As power came to play a larger role in the game, the tendency to bat home run hitters fourth developed accordingly.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The #3 and #4 hitters can often be switched in roles.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] For example, the 2011 Detroit Tigers had Miguel Cabrera as their #4 hitter but moved him to the #3 hitter after acquiring Prince Fielder as a free agent before the 2012 season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The fifth and sixth (and sometimes seventh) batters have traditionally been RBI men, with the main goal of driving runners home, especially with sacrifice flies.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The 3rd, 4th and 5th hitters in the lineup are called the "heart of the order", signifying their collective ability to get on base, hit for power and drive in runs.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Modern sabermetric baseball theories suggests that even the 5th and 6th batters should have high on-base percentages, though this approach has not been universally adopted.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The fifth batter is usually a team's second-best power hitter, and his purpose is often to "protect" the clean-up hitter in the batting order.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] He is expected to pose enough of a threat that the opposing team refrains from intentionally walking the clean-up hitter in potential scoring situations.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The sixth hitter serves as a backup to the fifth hitter in case he fails to score runs or to drive more in himself if another scoring opportunity presents itself.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The seventh and eighth batters are often not as powerful as the earlier batters, and do not have as high a batting average.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] They are often players who are in the lineup more because of their defensive ability (typically catcher, second baseman or shortstop) than their ability as hitters.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] They are still expected to produce (as is the case for *any* regular starter), but they have less pressure in those spots.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The main pressure on the eighth hitter comes when there are two outs: in this case, he must battle the pitcher to get on base so that the ninth hitter can come up.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] That way, even if the ninth hitter gets out, the top of the order comes up next.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Very often the #7 hitter is a catcher, commonly the slowest baserunner on a team whose lack of speed would contribute to a large number of double plays higher in the order even if he is a good hitter (Bill Freehan).
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The eighth batter is often a good contact hitter, and can be used as a back-up #2 hitter.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In leagues without designated hitters (DHs), the catcher often bats eighth, as they are often employed for their defensive skills and handling of the pitching staff, and tend to have a relatively low batting average.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] However, this is by no means always the case.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] The nine hole is traditionally meant for people that struggle to bat.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In leagues where the DH rule is not in effect, the starting pitcher almost always fills the ninth spot, although relief pitchers may occupy a different spot due to a double switch.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] If there is a man on first or second base with fewer than two outs when the ninth hitter is up, he almost always bunts.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] This has been used sparingly in the major leagues, but was notably employed by St.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Louis Cardinals manager Tony La Russa in the second half of the 1998 baseball season, and again in August 2007 and in 2008, and by Milwaukee Brewers manager Ned Yost in 2008.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] Chicago Cubs manager Joe Maddon placed the pitcher in the #8 spot during the beginning of the 2017 Cubs season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] On August 18, 1956, major league manager Bobby Bragan placed his best hitter in the leadoff position and the remainder of his lineup in descending batting average order.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] In his 1966 book, *Percentage Baseball*, Earnshaw Cook claimed that Bragan's lineup would result in 1 to 2 more wins per season.
[src:batting-order-baseball/batting-order-baseball] A computer simulation demonstrated the superiority of Bragan's lineup.
